# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: supply-chain-visibility
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The **bullwhip effect** is a supply chain phenomenon where orders to suppliers tend to have a larger variability than sales to buyers, which results in an amplified demand variability upstream.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In part, this results in increasing swings in inventory in response to shifts in consumer demand as one moves further up the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The concept first appeared in Jay Forrester's *Industrial Dynamics* (1961) and thus it is also known as the **Forrester effect**.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] It has been described as "the observed propensity for material orders to be more variable than demand signals and for this variability to increase the further upstream a company is in a supply chain".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Research at Stanford University helped incorporate the concept into supply chain vernacular using a story about Volvo.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Suffering a glut in green cars, sales and marketing developed a program to sell the excess inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] While successful in generating the desired market pull, manufacturing did not know about the promotional plans.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Instead, they read the increase in sales as an indication of growing demand for green cars and ramped up production.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Research indicates a fluctuation in point-of-sale demand of five percent will be interpreted by supply chain participants as a change in demand of up to forty percent.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Much like cracking a whip, a small flick of the wrist - a shift in point of sale demand - can cause a large motion at the end of the whip - manufacturers' responses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Because customer demand is rarely perfectly stable, businesses must forecast demand to properly position inventory and other resources.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Forecasts are based on statistics, and they are rarely perfectly accurate.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Because forecast errors are expected, companies often carry an inventory buffer called "safety stock".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Moving up the supply chain from end-consumer to raw materials supplier, each supply chain participant has greater observed variation in demand and thus greater need for safety stock.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In periods of rising demand, down-stream participants increase orders.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In periods of falling demand, orders fall or stop, thereby not reducing inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The effect is that variations are amplified as one moves upstream in the supply chain (further from the customer).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This sequence of events is well simulated by the beer distribution game that was developed by MIT Sloan School of Management in the 1960s.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Research on supply-chain complexity has identified additional mechanisms through which variability may propagate through supply networks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The "supply chain complexity triangle" describes uncertainty as arising from the interaction of demand amplification, deterministic chaos, and parallel interactions between supply-chain channels.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In addition to demand amplification, the framework highlights how disturbances may spread through interconnected channels and nonlinear feedback processes within the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The causes can further be divided into behavioral and operational causes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The first theories focusing onto the bullwhip effect were mainly focusing on the irrational behavior of the human in the supply chain, highlighting them as the main cause of the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Since the 90's, the studies evolved, placing the supply chain's malfunctioning at the heart of their studies abandoning the human factors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Previous control-theoretic models have identified as causes the tradeoff between stationary and dynamic performance as well as the use of independent controllers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] (2017), one of the main behavioral causes that contribute to the bullwhip effect is the under-estimation of the pipeline.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In addition, the complementary bias, over-estimation of the pipeline, also has a negative effect under such conditions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Nevertheless, it has been shown that when the demand stream is stationary, the system is relatively robust to this bias.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In such situations, it has been found that biased policies (both under-estimating and over-estimating the pipeline) perform just as well as unbiased policies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Human factors influencing the behavior in supply chains are largely unexplored.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] However, studies suggest that people with increased need for safety and security seem to perform worse than risk-takers in a simulated supply chain environment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] People with high self-efficacy experience less trouble handling the bullwhip-effect in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] (1997) study found that the bullwhip effect did not solely result from irrational decision making: it found that under some circumstances it is rational for a firm to order with greater variability than variability of demand, i.e., distort demand and cause the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] They established a list of four major factors which cause the bullwhip effect: demand signal processing, rationing game, order batching, and price variations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This list has become a standard and is used as a framework to identify bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In addition to greater safety stocks, the described effect can lead to either inefficient production or excessive inventory, as each producer needs to fulfill the demand of its customers in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This also leads to a low utilization of the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In spite of having safety stocks there is still the hazard of stock-outs which result in poor customer service and lost sales.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In addition to the (financially) hard measurable consequences of poor customer services and the damage to public image and loyalty, an organization has to cope with the ramifications of failed fulfillment which may include contractual penalties.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Moreover, repeated hiring and dismissal of employees to manage the demand variability induces further costs due to training and possible lay-offs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Since the Corona virus pandemic, many companies have been dealing with a strong bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This problem is directly linked to the ongoing impacts of the Corona virus pandemic, even though it is further exacerbated by the ever changing nature of demand for consumer goods .
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] These shortages caused companies to order even more as they reasoned this would give them a larger share of the pie.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] As lead times return to normal, however, all these products are finally flowing in but demand drops for these same products leading to large excess inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] In other words, retailers or customers order more based on slight sales increases or increases in demand, which causes each entity in the supply chain to request or produce more in anticipation of higher demands, at the end creating a ripple effect in the supply and logistics chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] For instance, during the pandemic, people suddenly bought lots of essential and safety-related goods like nose masks, hand sanitizers, causing big fluctuations in demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] As each level in the supply chain reacted to these extra demands, they tended to over-order to prevent stockouts, which made the problem worse down to the manufacturer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This led to excessive investment in inventory, lost revenue, declines in customer service, delayed schedules, and even layoffs or bankruptcies and global freight services delivery delays as was the case for e-commerce platforms like Amazon and Alibaba.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] During the COVID-19 pandemic, they faced global shipping delays, increased freight costs, and lead-time uncertainties.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] When shipping and production are delayed, downstream partners, retailers and consumers often order more just in case, thereby further enhancing the ripple effects of the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Information sharing across the supply chain is an effective strategy to mitigate the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] For example, it has been successfully implemented in Wal-Mart's distribution system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Individual Wal-Mart stores transmit point-of-sale (POS) data from the cash register back to corporate headquarters several times a day.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This demand information is used to queue shipments from the Wal-Mart distribution center to the store and from the supplier to the Wal-Mart distribution center.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The result is near-perfect visibility of customer demand and inventory movement throughout the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Better information leads to better inventory positioning and lower costs throughout the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Another recommended strategy to limit the bullwhip effect is order smoothing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Previous research has demonstrated that order smoothing and the bullwhip effect are concurrent in industry.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] It has been proved that order smoothing is beneficial for the system's performance when the demand is stationary.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] However, its impact is limited to the worst-case order amplification when the demand is unpredictable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Having said that, dynamic analysis reveals that order smoothing can degrade performance in the presence of demand shocks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The opposite bias (i.e., over-reaction to mismatches), on the other hand, degrades the stationary performance but can increase dynamic performance; controlled over-reaction can aid the system reach its new goals quickly.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] The system, nevertheless, is considerably sensitive to that behaviour; extreme over-reaction significantly reduces performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Overall, unbiased policies offer in general good results under a large range of demand types.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Although these policies do not result in the best performance under certain criteria.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] It is always possible to find a biased policy that outperforms an unbiased policy for any one performance metric.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Many studies demonstrate the bullwhip effect in a supply chain from different perspectives, including information sharing, information distortion, bankruptcy events and systematic risk.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Most of them devote themselves to exploring the bullwhip effect from the perspectives of inventory flow risk and information flow risk rather than that of cash flow risk.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] For a firm's internal liquidity risk (Chen et al., 2011), it is an appropriate proxy for a firm's financial risk.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] This is more generally modelled in Proselkov's work in 2023, which uses complex adaptive systems modelling to study cascade failures as a consequence of financial bullwhips.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] Specifically, they create an agent-based supply network simulation model capturing the behaviours of companies with asymmetric power dynamics with their partners.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/bullwhip-effect] To remain operational, they maximise their liquidity by negotiating longer repayment terms and cheaper financing, thus distributing risk onto weaker companies and propagating financial stress.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Decisions about distribution need to be taken in line with a company's overall strategic vision and mission.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Developing a coherent distribution plan is a central component of strategic planning.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] At the strategic level, as well as deciding whether to distribute directly or via a distribution network, there are three broad approaches to distribution, namely mass, selective and exclusive distribution.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The number and type of intermediaries selected largely depends on the strategic approach.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The overall distribution channel should also add value to the consumer overall.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Distribution is fundamentally concerned with ensuring that products reach target customers in the most direct and cost-efficient manner.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In the case of services, distribution is principally concerned with access.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Before designing a distribution system, the supplier needs to determine what distribution channel to achieve in broad terms.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The approach to distributing products or services depends on a number of factors including the type of product, especially perishability; the market served; the geographic scope of operations and the firm's overall mission and vision.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The process of setting out a broad statement of the aims and objectives of a distribution channel is a strategic level decision.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In consumer markets, another key strategic level decision is whether to use a push or pull strategy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In a *push strategy*, the marketer uses intensive advertising and incentives aimed at distributors, especially retailers and wholesalers, with the expectation that they will stock the product or brand, and that consumers will purchase it when they see it in stores.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In contrast, in a *pull strategy*, the marketer promotes the product directly to consumers hoping that they will pressure retailers to stock the product or brand, thereby pulling it through the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The choice of a push or pull strategy has important implications for advertising and promotion.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Distribution of products takes place through a marketing channel, also known as a distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A marketing channel is the people, organizations, and activities necessary to transfer the ownership of goods from the point of production to the point of consumption.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] It is the way products get to the end-user, the consumer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] This is mostly accomplished through merchant retailers or wholesalers or, in the international context, by importers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In certain specialist markets, agents or brokers may become involved in the marketing channel: for example in the insurance sector, the European Union has noted that "insurance and reinsurance intermediaries play a central role in the distribution of insurance and reinsurance products" .
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The EU introduced the Insurance Distribution Directive in 2016 to enhance a level of harmonisation in this market across EU member states.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A firm can design any number of channels they require to reach customers efficiently and effectively.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Channels can be distinguished by the number of intermediaries between producer and consumer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] If there are no intermediaries then this is known as a *zero-level* distribution system or direct marketing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A *level one* (sometimes called *one-tier*) channel has a single intermediary.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A *level two* (alternatively a *two-tier*) channel has two intermediaries, and so on.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] This flow is typically represented as being manufacturer to retailer to consumer, but may involve other types of intermediaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In practice, distribution systems for perishable goods tend to be shorter - direct or single intermediary, because of the need to reduce the time a product spends in transit or in storage.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In other cases, distribution systems can become quite complex involving many levels and different types of intermediaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In practice, many organizations use a mix of different channels; a direct sales force may call on larger customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] This may be complemented with other agents to cover smaller customers and prospects.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] When a single organization uses a variety of different channels to reach its markets, this is known as a *multi-channel* distribution network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In addition, online retailing or e-commerce is leading to disintermediation, the removal of intermediaries from a supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Retailing via smartphone or m-commerce is also a growth area.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The firm's marketing department needs to design the most suitable channels for the firm's products, then select appropriate channel members or intermediaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] An organization may need to train staff of intermediaries and motivate the intermediary to sell the firm's products.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The firm should monitor the channel's performance over time and modify the channel to enhance performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] To motivate intermediaries the firm can use positive actions, such as offering higher margins to the intermediary, special deals, premiums and allowances for advertising or display.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] On the other hand, negative actions may be necessary, such as threatening to cut back on margin, or hold back delivery of product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Care must be exercised when considering negative actions as these may fall foul of regulations and can contribute to a public backlash and a public relations disaster.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Manufacturer complacency has been highlighted as a risk leading distributors to move their business to other supply lines.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Channel conflict can arise when one intermediary's actions prevent another intermediary from achieving their objectives.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Vertical channel conflict occurs between the levels within a channel, and horizontal channel conflict occurs between intermediaries at the same level within a channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Channel conflict is a perennial problem.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] There are risks that a powerful channel member may coordinate the interests of the channel for personal gain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Territories are often seen as a source of conflict, sometimes because boundaries are only loosely defined.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Hart refers to the extensive development of these guilds and the "Training Schools" which they operated, converting these into a radio-based program from 1942.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Hart, who worked for the supplier, put this experience forward to the American Marketing Association as "an outstanding example of manufacturer-distributor collaboration on an industry-wide basis".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Companies wishing to grow through sales to new markets may need to identify and develop relationships with local distributors, for example to support export to new markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] In southeast Asia, for example, many distributors have a head office in Singapore which can be used by manufacturers outside the region to increase their regional market penetration and grow sales.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Channel-switching is the action of consumers switching from one type of channel intermediary to a different type of intermediary for their purchases.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Examples include switching from brick-and-mortar stores to online catalogues and e-commerce providers; switching from grocery stores to convenience stores or switching from top tier department stores to mass market discount outlets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A number of factors have led to an increase in channel switching behaviour; the growth of e-commerce, the globalization of markets, the advent of category killers (such as Officeworks and Kids 'R Us) as well as changes in the legal or statutory environment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] For the consumer, channel switching offers a more diverse shopping experience, which may concern some sellers by its potential to erode market share.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Evidence of channel switching can suggest that disruptive forces are at play, and that consumer behaviour is undergoing fundamental changes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] A consumer may be prompted to switch channels when the product or service can be found at cheaper prices, when superior models become available, when a wider range is offered, or simply because it is more convenient to shop through a different channel (e.g. online or one-stop shopping).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] As a hedge against market share losses due to switching behaviour, some retailers engage in multi-channel retailing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The emergence of a service-dominant logic perspective has focused scholarly attention on how distribution networks serve to create customer value and to consider how value is co-created by all the players within the distribution chain, including the value created by customers themselves.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] This emphasis on value-creation is contributing to a change in terminology surrounding distribution processes; "distribution networks" are often termed *value-chains* while "distribution centers" are often termed *customer fulfillment centers*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] For example, the retail giant Amazon, which utilizes both direct online distribution alongside bricks and mortar stores, now calls its distribution centers "customer fulfillment centers".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Although the term "customer fulfillment center" has been criticized on the grounds that it is a neologism, its use is becoming increasingly mainstream as it slowly makes its way into introductory marketing textbooks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Disintermediation occurs when manufacturers or service providers eliminate intermediaries from the distribution network and deal directly with purchasers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Disintermediation is found in industries where radically new types of channel intermediaries displace traditional distributors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] The widespread public acceptance of online shopping has been a major trigger for disintermediation in some industries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/distribution-marketing] Certain types of traditional intermediaries are dropping by the wayside.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory management is a discipline primarily about specifying the shape and placement of stocked goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is required at different locations within a facility or within many locations of a supply network to precede the regular and planned course of production and stock of materials.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In the context of a manufacturing production system, inventory refers to all work that has occurred—raw materials, partially finished products, finished products prior to sale and departure from the manufacturing system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In the context of services, inventory refers to all work done prior to sale, including partially process information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Seasonal demand: Demands varies periodically, but producers capacity is fixed.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This can lead to stock accumulation, consider for example how goods consumed only in holidays can lead to accumulation of large stocks on the anticipation of future consumption.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Uncertainty: Inventories are maintained as buffers to meet uncertainties in demand, supply and movements of goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Economies of scale: Ideal condition of "one unit at a time at a place where a user needs it, when he needs it" principle tends to incur lots of costs in terms of logistics.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] So bulk buying, movement and storing brings in economies of scale, thus inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Appreciation in value: In some situations, some stock gains the required value when it is kept for some time to allow it reach the desired standard for consumption, or for production.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] For example, beer in the brewing industry.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] All these stock reasons can apply to any owner or product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Reorder level: Reorder level refers to the point when a company place an order to re-fill the stocks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Reorder point depends on the inventory policy of a company.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Some companies place orders when the inventory level is lower than a certain quantity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Some companies place orders periodically.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Cycle stock: Used in batch processes, cycle stock is the available inventory, excluding buffer stock.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] De-coupling: Buffer stock held between the machines in a single process which serves as a buffer for the next one allowing smooth flow of work instead of waiting the previous or next machine in the same process.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Anticipation stock: Building up extra stock for periods of increased demand—e.g., ice cream for summer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Pipeline stock: Goods still in transit or in the process of distribution; e.g., they have left the factory but not arrived at the customer yet.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Often calculated as: *Average Daily / Weekly usage quantity X Lead time in days + Safety stock*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] While accountants often discuss inventory in terms of goods for sale, organizations—manufacturers, service-providers and not-for-profits—also have inventories (fixtures, equipment, furniture, supplies, parts, etc.) that they do not intend to sell.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Manufacturers', distributors', and wholesalers' inventory tends to cluster in warehouses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Retailers' inventory may exist in a warehouse or in a shop or store accessible to customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventories not intended for sale to customers or to clients may be held in any premises an organization uses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Stock ties up cash and, if uncontrolled, it will be impossible to know the actual level of stocks and therefore difficult to keep the costs associated with holding too much or too little inventory under control.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] A canned food manufacturer's materials inventory includes the ingredients to form the foods to be canned, empty cans and their lids (or coils of steel or aluminum for constructing those components), labels, and anything else (solder, glue, etc.) that will form part of a finished can.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The firm's work in process includes those materials from the time of release to the work floor until they become complete and ready for sale to wholesale or retail customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This may be vats of prepared food, filled cans not yet labeled or sub-assemblies of food components.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It may also include finished cans that are not yet packaged into cartons or pallets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Its finished good inventory consists of all the filled and labeled cans of food in its warehouse that it has manufactured and wishes to sell to food distributors (wholesalers), to grocery stores (retailers), and even perhaps to consumers through arrangements like factory stores and outlet centers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The partially completed work (or work in process) is a measure of inventory built during the work execution of a capital project, such as encountered in civilian infrastructure construction or oil and gas.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory may not only reflect physical items (such as materials, parts, partially-finished sub-assemblies) but also knowledge work-in-process (such as partially completed engineering designs of components and assemblies to be fabricated).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Specific problems arise in the defence field regarding the maintenance of adequate stocks of supplies and spare parts to take account of unknown deployment requirements while avoiding risks of obsolescence.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Singh in a letter to former Prime Minister Manmohan Singh.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] A "virtual inventory" (also known as a "bank inventory") enables a group of users to share common parts, especially where their availability at short notice may be critical but they are unlikely to required by more than a few bank members at any one time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Virtual inventory also allows distributors and fulfilment houses to ship goods to retailers direct from stock, regardless of whether the stock is held in a retail store, stock room or warehouse.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Virtual inventories allow participants to access a wider mix of products and to reduce the risks involved in carrying inventory for which expected demand does not materialise.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory proportionality is the goal of demand-driven inventory management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The primary optimal outcome is to have the same number of days' (or hours', etc.) worth of inventory on hand across all products so that the time of runout of all products would be simultaneous.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In such a case, there is no "excess inventory", that is, inventory that would be left over of another product when the first product runs out.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Holding excess inventory is sub-optimal because the money spent to obtain and the cost of holding it could have been utilized better elsewhere, i.e. to the product that just ran out.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The secondary goal of inventory proportionality is inventory minimization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] By integrating accurate demand forecasting with inventory management, rather than only looking at past averages, a much more accurate and optimal outcome is expected.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Integrating demand forecasting into inventory management in this way also allows for the prediction of the "can fit" point when inventory storage is limited on a per-product basis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] One early example of inventory proportionality used in a retail application in the United States was for motor fuel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Motor fuel (e.g. gasoline) is generally stored in underground storage tanks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The motorists do not know whether they are buying gasoline off the top or bottom of the tank, nor need they care.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Additionally, these storage tanks have a maximum capacity and cannot be overfilled.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory proportionality is used to balance the inventories of the different grades of motor fuel, each stored in dedicated tanks, in proportion to the sales of each grade.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Excess inventory is not seen or valued by the consumer, so it is simply cash "sunk into the ground".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory proportionality minimizes the amount of excess inventory carried in underground storage tanks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This application for motor fuel was first developed and implemented by Petrolsoft Corporation in 1990 for Chevron Products Company.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Most major oil companies use such systems today.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The use of inventory proportionality in the United States is thought to have been inspired by Japanese just-in-time parts inventory management made famous by Toyota Motors in the 1980s.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It seems that around 1880 there was a change in manufacturing practice from companies with relatively homogeneous lines of products to horizontally integrated companies with unprecedented diversity in processes and products.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Those companies (especially in metalworking) attempted to achieve success through economies of scope—the gains of jointly producing two or more products in one facility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The managers now needed information on the effect of product-mix decisions on overall profits and therefore needed accurate product-cost information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] A variety of attempts to achieve this were unsuccessful due to the huge overhead of the information processing of the time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] However, the burgeoning need for financial reporting after 1900 created unavoidable pressure for financial accounting of stock and the management need to cost manage products became overshadowed.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In particular, it was the need for audited accounts that sealed the fate of managerial cost accounting.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The dominance of financial reporting accounting over management accounting remains to this day with few exceptions, and the financial reporting definitions of 'cost' have distorted effective management 'cost' accounting since that time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Cost of goods available − cost of ending inventory at the end of the period = cost of goods sold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The benefit of these formulas is that the first absorbs all overheads of production and raw material costs into a value of inventory for reporting.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The second formula then creates the new start point for the next period and gives a figure to be subtracted from the sales price to determine some form of sales-margin figure.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Manufacturing management is more interested in *inventory turnover ratio* or *average days to sell inventory* since it tells them something about relative inventory levels.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This ratio estimates how many times the inventory turns over a year.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This number tells how much cash/goods are tied up waiting for the process and is a critical measure of process reliability and effectiveness.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] So a factory with two inventory turns has six months stock on hand, which is generally not a good figure (depending upon the industry), whereas a factory that moves from six turns to twelve turns has probably improved effectiveness by 100%.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This improvement will have some negative results in the financial reporting, since the 'value' now stored in the factory as inventory is reduced.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] While these accounting measures of inventory are very useful because of their simplicity, they are also fraught with the danger of their own assumptions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] There are, in fact, so many things that can vary hidden under this appearance of simplicity that a variety of 'adjusting' assumptions may be used.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory Turn is a financial accounting tool for evaluating inventory and it is not necessarily a management tool.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory management should be forward looking.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The methodology applied is based on historical cost of goods sold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The ratio may not be able to reflect the usability of future production demand, as well as customer demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Business models, including Just in Time (JIT) Inventory, Vendor Managed Inventory (VMI) and Customer Managed Inventory (CMI), attempt to minimize on-hand inventory and increase inventory turns.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] VMI and CMI have gained considerable attention due to the success of third-party vendors who offer added expertise and knowledge that organizations may not possess.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory management also involves risk which varies depending upon a firm's position in the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory exposure, which has been defined as "the amount of committed inventory within the total supply chain based upon expected demand and the cumulative lead-times associated with the current supply chain", can be measured in several ways.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Some typical measures of inventory exposure are width of commitment, time or duration, and depth.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Modern inventory management is online oriented and more viable in digital.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This type of dynamics order management will require end-to-end visibility, collaboration across fulfillment processes, real-time data automation among different companies, and integration among multiple systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Each country has its own rules about accounting for inventory that fit with their financial-reporting rules.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] For example, organizations in the U.S. define **inventory** to suit their needs within US Generally Accepted Accounting Practices (GAAP), the rules defined by the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) (and others) and enforced by the U.S.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) and other federal and state agencies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Other countries often have similar arrangements but with their own accounting standards and national agencies instead.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is intentional that while financial accounting uses standards that allow the public to compare firms' performance, cost accounting functions internally to an organization, and potentially with much greater flexibility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] A discussion of inventory from standard and theory of constraints-based (throughput) cost accounting perspective follows some examples and a discussion of inventory from a financial accounting perspective.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The internal costing/valuation of inventory can be complex.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Whereas in the past most enterprises ran simple, one-process factories, such enterprises are quite probably in the minority in the 21st century.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Where 'one process' factories exist, there is a market for the goods created, which establishes an independent market value for the good.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Today, with multistage-process companies, there is much inventory that would once have been finished goods which is now held as 'work in process' (WIP).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This needs to be valued in the accounts, but the valuation is a management decision since there is no market for the partially finished product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This somewhat arbitrary 'valuation' of WIP combined with the allocation of overheads to it has led to some unintended and undesirable results.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] An organization's inventory can appear a mixed blessing, since it counts as an asset on the balance sheet, but it also ties up money that could serve for other purposes and requires additional expense for its protection.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory may also cause significant tax expenses, depending on particular countries' laws regarding depreciation of inventory, as in Thor Power Tool Company v.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory appears as a current asset on an organization's balance sheet because the organization can, in principle, turn it into cash by selling it.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Some organizations hold larger inventories than their operations require in order to inflate their apparent asset value and their perceived profitability.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In addition to the money tied up by acquiring inventory, inventory also brings associated costs for warehouse space, for utilities, and for insurance to cover staff to handle and protect it from fire and other disasters, obsolescence, shrinkage (theft and errors), and others.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Such holding costs can mount up: between a third and a half of its acquisition value per year.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Businesses that stock too little inventory cannot take advantage of large orders from customers if they cannot deliver.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The conflicting objectives of cost control and customer service often put an organization's financial and operating managers against its sales and marketing departments.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Salespeople, in particular, often receive sales-commission payments, so unavailable goods may reduce their potential personal income.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This conflict can be minimised by reducing production time to being near or less than customers' expected delivery time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This effort, known as "Lean production" will significantly reduce working capital tied up in inventory and reduce manufacturing costs (See the Toyota Production System).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] By helping the organization to make better decisions, the accountants can help the public sector to change in a very positive way that delivers increased value for the taxpayer's investment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It can also help to incentive's progress and to ensure that reforms are sustainable and effective in the long term, by ensuring that success is appropriately recognized in both the formal and informal reward systems of the organization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] To say that they have a key role to play is an understatement.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Finance is connected to most, if not all, of the key business processes within the organization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It should be steering the stewardship and accountability systems that ensure that the organization is conducting its business in an appropriate, ethical manner.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is critical that these foundations are firmly laid.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] So often they are the litmus test by which public confidence in the institution is either won or lost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Finance should also be providing the information, analysis and advice to enable the organizations' service managers to operate effectively.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This goes beyond the traditional preoccupation with budgets—how much have we spent so far, how much do we have left to spend?
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is about helping the organization to better understand its own performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] That means making the connections and understanding the relationships between given inputs—the resources brought to bear—and the outputs and outcomes that they achieve.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is also about understanding and actively managing risks within the organization and its activities.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] When a merchant buys goods from inventory, the value of the inventory account is reduced by the cost of goods sold (COGS).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This is simple where the cost has not varied across those held in stock; but where it has, then an agreed method must be derived to evaluate it.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] For inventory items that one cannot track individually, accountants must choose a method that fits the nature of the sale.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Two popular methods in use are: FIFO (first in, first out) and LIFO (last in, first out).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] FIFO treats the first unit that arrived in inventory as the first one sold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] FIFO results in inventory on the balance sheet reflecting the most recent purchase costs, thereby providing a closer approximation of current inventory value.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] LIFO considers the last unit arriving in inventory as the first one sold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Which method an accountant selects can have a significant effect on net income and book value and, in turn, on taxation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Using LIFO accounting for inventory, a company generally reports lower net income and lower book value, due to the effects of inflation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This generally results in lower taxation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Due to LIFO's potential to skew inventory value, UK GAAP and IAS have effectively banned LIFO inventory accounting.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] LIFO accounting is permitted in the United States subject to section 472 of the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Standard cost accounting uses ratios called efficiencies that compare the labour and materials actually used to produce a good with those that the same goods would have required under "standard" conditions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] As long as actual and standard conditions are similar, few problems arise.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Unfortunately, standard cost accounting methods developed about 100 years ago, when labor comprised the most important cost in manufactured goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Standard methods continue to emphasize labor efficiency even though that resource now constitutes a (very) small part of cost in most cases.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Standard cost accounting can hurt managers, workers, and firms in several ways.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] For example, a policy decision to increase inventory can harm a manufacturing manager's performance evaluation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Increasing inventory requires increased production, which means that processes must operate at higher rates.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] When (not if) something goes wrong, the process takes longer and uses more than the standard labor time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The manager appears responsible for the excess, even though s/he has no control over the production requirement or the problem.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In adverse economic times, firms use the same efficiencies to downsize, rightsize, or otherwise reduce their labor force.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Workers laid off under those circumstances have even less control over excess inventory and cost efficiencies than their managers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Many financial and cost accountants have agreed for many years on the desirability of replacing standard cost accounting.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] They have not, however, found a successor.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Goldratt developed the theory of constraints in part to address the cost-accounting problems in what he calls the "cost world".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] He offers a substitute, called throughput accounting, which uses throughput (money for goods sold to customers) in place of output (goods produced that may sell or may boost inventory) and considers labor as a fixed rather than as a variable cost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] He defines inventory simply as everything the organization owns that it plans to sell, including buildings, machinery, and many other things in addition to the categories listed here.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Finished goods inventories remain balance-sheet assets, but labor-efficiency ratios no longer evaluate managers and workers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Instead of an incentive to reduce labor cost, throughput accounting focuses attention on the relationships between throughput (revenue or income) on one hand and controllable operating expenses and changes in inventory on the other.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventories also play an important role in national accounts and the analysis of the business cycle.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Some short-term macroeconomic fluctuations are attributed to the inventory cycle.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Also known as distressed or expired stock, distressed inventory is inventory whose potential to be sold at a normal cost has passed or will soon pass.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In certain industries it could also mean that the stock is or will soon be impossible to sell.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Examples of distressed inventory include products which have reached their expiry date, or have reached a date in advance of expiry at which the planned market will no longer purchase them (e.g.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] 3 months left to expiry), clothing which is out of fashion, music which is no longer popular and old newspapers or magazines.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It also includes computer or consumer-electronic equipment which is obsolete or discontinued and whose manufacturer is unable to support it, along with products which use that type of equipment e.g.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] In 2001, Cisco wrote off inventory worth US$2.25 billion due to duplicate orders.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This is considered one of the biggest inventory write-offs in business history.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Stock rotation is the practice of changing the way inventory is displayed on a regular basis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This is most commonly used in hospitality and retail - particularity where food products are sold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] For example, in the case of supermarkets that a customer frequents on a regular basis, the customer may know exactly what they want and where it is.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This results in many customers going straight to the product they seek and do not look at other items on sale.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] To discourage this practice, stores will rotate the location of stock to encourage customers to look through the entire store.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This is in hopes the customer will pick up items they would not normally see.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory credit refers to the use of stock, or inventory, as collateral to raise finance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Where banks may be reluctant to accept traditional collateral, for example in developing countries where land title may be lacking, inventory credit is a potentially important way of overcoming financing constraints.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] This is not a new concept; archaeological evidence suggests that it was practiced in Ancient Rome.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Obtaining finance against stocks of a wide range of products held in a bonded warehouse is common in much of the world.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] It is, for example, used with Parmesan cheese in Italy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Inventory credit on the basis of stored agricultural produce is widely used in Latin American countries and in some Asian countries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] A precondition for such credit is that banks must be confident that the stored product will be available if they need to call on the collateral; this implies the existence of a reliable network of certified warehouses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] Banks also face problems in valuing the inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/inventory] The possibility of sudden falls in commodity prices means that they are usually reluctant to lend more than about 60% of the value of the inventory at the time of the loan.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Passive tags are powered by energy from the RFID reader's interrogating radio waves.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Active tags are powered by a battery and thus can be read at a greater range from the RFID reader, up to hundreds of meters.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Unlike a barcode, the tag does not need to be within the line of sight of the reader, so it may be embedded in the tracked object.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID is one method of automatic identification and data capture (AIDC).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] For example, an RFID tag attached to an automobile during production can be used to track its progress through the assembly line, RFID-tagged pharmaceuticals can be tracked through warehouses, and implanting RFID microchips in livestock and pets enables positive identification of animals.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tags can also be used in shops to expedite checkout, and to prevent theft by customers and employees.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since RFID tags can be attached to physical money, clothing, and possessions, or implanted in animals and people, the possibility of reading personally linked information without consent has raised privacy concerns.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These concerns resulted in standard specifications development addressing privacy and security issues.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2014, the world RFID market was worth US$8.89 billion, up from US$7.77 billion in 2013 and US$6.96 billion in 2012.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This figure includes tags, readers, and software/services for RFID cards, labels, fobs, and all other form factors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The market value is expected to rise from US$12.08 billion in 2020 to US$16.23 billion by 2029.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2024, about 50 billion tag chips were sold, according to Atlas RFID and RAIN Alliance webinars in July 2025.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 1945, Leon Theremin invented the "Thing", a listening device for the Soviet Union which retransmitted incident radio waves with the added audio information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Sound waves vibrated a diaphragm, which slightly altered the shape of the resonator, which modulated the reflected radio frequency.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Even though this device was a covert listening device, rather than an identification tag, it is considered to be a predecessor of RFID because it was passive, being energised and activated by waves from an outside source.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Similar technology, such as the Identification friend or foe transponder, was routinely used by the Allies and Germany in World War II to identify aircraft as friendly or hostile.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Transponders are still used by most powered aircraft.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Mario Cardullo's device, patented on January 23, 1973, was the first true ancestor of modern RFID, as it was a passive radio transponder with memory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The initial device was passive, powered by the interrogating signal, and was demonstrated in 1971 to the New York Port Authority and other potential users.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It consisted of a transponder with 16 bit memory for use as a toll device.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The basic Cardullo patent covers the use of radio frequency (RF), sound and light as transmission carriers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 1973, an early demonstration of *reflected power* (modulated backscatter) RFID tags, both passive and semi-passive, was performed by Steven Depp, Alfred Koelle and Robert Freyman at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The portable system operated at 915 MHz and used 12-bit tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This technique is used by the majority of today's UHFID and microwave RFID tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 1983, the first patent to be associated with the abbreviation RFID was granted to Charles Walton.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 1996, the first patent for a batteryless RFID passive tag with limited interference was granted to David Everett, John Frech, Theodore Wright, and Kelly Rodriguez.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A radio-frequency identification system uses *tags*, or *labels* attached to the objects to be identified.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Two-way radio transmitter-receivers called *interrogators* or *readers* send a signal to the tag and read its response.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag information is stored in non-volatile memory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The RFID tags includes either fixed or programmable logic for processing the transmission and sensor data, respectively.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags can be either passive, active or battery-assisted passive.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An active tag has an on-board battery and periodically transmits its ID signal.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A battery-assisted passive tag has a small battery on board and is activated when in the presence of an RFID reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A passive tag is cheaper and smaller because it has no battery; instead, the tag uses the radio energy transmitted by the reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] However, to operate a passive tag, it must be illuminated with a power level roughly a thousand times stronger than an active tag for signal transmission.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tags may either be read-only, having a factory-assigned serial number that is used as a key into a database, or may be read/write, where object-specific data can be written into the tag by the system user.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Field programmable tags may be write-once, read-multiple; blank tags may be written with an electronic product code by the user.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The RFID tag receives the message and then responds with its identification and other information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This may be only a unique tag serial number, or may be product-related information such as a stock number, lot or batch number, production date, or other specific information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since tags have individual serial numbers, the RFID system design can discriminate among several tags that might be within the range of the RFID reader and read them simultaneously.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID systems can be classified by the type of tag and reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Fixed readers are set up to create a specific interrogation zone which can be tightly controlled.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This allows a highly defined reading area for when tags go in and out of the interrogation zone.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Mobile readers may be handheld or mounted on carts or vehicles.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Signaling between the reader and the tag is done in several different incompatible ways, depending on the frequency band used by the tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tags operating on LF and HF bands are, in terms of radio wavelength, very close to the reader antenna because they are only a small percentage of a wavelength away.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In this near field region, the tag is closely coupled electrically with the transmitter in the reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag can modulate the field produced by the reader by changing the electrical loading the tag represents.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] By switching between lower and higher relative loads, the tag produces a change that the reader can detect.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] At UHF and higher frequencies, the tag is more than one radio wavelength away from the reader, requiring a different approach.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Active tags may contain functionally separated transmitters and receivers, and the tag need not respond on a frequency related to the reader's interrogation signal.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An Electronic Product Code (EPC) is one common type of data stored in a tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] When written into the tag by an RFID printer, the tag contains a 96-bit string of data.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The first eight bits are a header which identifies the version of the protocol.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The next 28 bits identify the organization that manages the data for this tag; the organization number is assigned by the EPCGlobal consortium.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The next 24 bits are an object class, identifying the kind of product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The last 36 bits are a unique serial number for a particular tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These last two fields are set by the organization that issued the tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Rather like a URL, the total electronic product code number can be used as a key into a global database to uniquely identify a particular product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Often more than one tag will respond to a tag reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] For example, many individual products with tags may be shipped in a common box or on a common pallet.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Collision detection is important to allow reading of data in these situations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Two different types of protocols are used to singulate a particular tag, allowing its data to be read in the midst of many similar tags: In a Slotted Aloha system, the reader broadcasts an initialization command and a parameter that the tags individually use to pseudo-randomly delay their responses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] When using an **adaptive binary tree** protocol, the reader sends an initialization symbol and then transmits one bit of ID data at a time; only tags with matching bits respond, and eventually only one tag matches the complete ID string.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Both methods have drawbacks when used with many tags or with multiple overlapping readers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A group of tags has to be illuminated by the interrogating signal just like a single tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This is not a challenge concerning energy, but with respect to visibility; if any of the tags are shielded by other tags, they might not be sufficiently illuminated to return a sufficient response.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The response conditions for inductively coupled HF RFID tags and coil antennas in magnetic fields appear better than for UHF or SHF dipole fields, but then distance limits apply and may prevent success.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Under operational conditions, bulk reading is not reliable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Bulk reading can be a rough guide for logistics decisions, but due to a high proportion of reading failures, it is not currently suitable for inventory management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] However, when a single RFID tag might be seen as not guaranteeing a proper read, multiple RFID tags, where at least one will respond, may be a safer approach for detecting a known grouping of objects.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In this respect, bulk reading is a fuzzy method for process support.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] From the perspective of cost and effect, bulk reading is not reported as an economical approach to secure process control in logistics.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are easy to conceal or incorporate in other items.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] For example, in 2009, researchers at Bristol University successfully glued RFID micro-transponders to live ants in order to study their behavior.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This trend towards increasingly miniaturized RFIDs is likely to continue as technology advances.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Hitachi holds the record for the smallest RFID chip, at 0.05 mm × 0.05 mm.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This is 1/64th the size of the previous record holder, the mu-chip.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Manufacture is enabled by using the silicon-on-insulator (SOI) process.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These dust-sized chips can store 38-digit numbers using 128-bit Read Only Memory (ROM).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A major challenge is the attachment of antennas, thus limiting read range to only millimeters.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In early 2020, MIT researchers demonstrated a terahertz frequency identification (TFID) tag that is barely 1 square millimeter in size.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The devices are essentially a piece of silicon that are inexpensive, small, and function like larger RFID tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Because of the small size, manufacturers could tag any product and track logistics information for minimal cost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An RFID tag can be affixed to an object and used to track tools, equipment, inventory, assets, people, or other objects.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID offers advantages over manual systems or use of barcodes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag can be read if passed near a reader, even if it is covered by the object or not visible.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag can be read inside a case, carton, box or other container, and unlike barcodes, RFID tags can be read hundreds at a time; barcodes can only be read one at a time using current devices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Some RFID tags, such as battery-assisted passive tags, are also able to monitor temperature and humidity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2011, the cost of passive tags started at US$0.09 each; special tags, meant to be mounted on metal or withstand gamma sterilization, could cost up to US$5.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Active tags for tracking containers, medical assets, or monitoring environmental conditions in data centers started at US$50 and could be over US$100 each.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Battery-Assisted Passive (BAP) tags were in the US$3–10 range.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2010, three factors drove a significant increase in RFID usage: decreased cost of equipment and tags, increased performance to a reliability of 99.9%, and a stable international standard around HF and UHF passive RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The adoption of these standards were driven by EPCglobal, a joint venture between GS1 and GS1 US, which were responsible for driving global adoption of the barcode in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The EPCglobal Network was developed by the Auto-ID Center.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID provides a way for organizations to identify and manage stock, tools and equipment (asset tracking), etc. without manual data entry.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Manufactured products such as automobiles or garments can be tracked through the factory and through shipping to the customer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Automatic identification with RFID can be used for inventory systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Many organisations require that their vendors place RFID tags on all shipments to improve supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Warehouse Management System incorporate this technology to speed up the receiving and delivery of the products and reduce the cost of labor needed in their warehouses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID is used for item-level tagging in retail stores.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This can enable more accurate and lower-labor-cost supply chain and store inventory tracking, as is done at Lululemon, though physically locating items in stores requires more expensive technology.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags can be used at checkout; for example, at some stores of the French retailer Decathlon, customers perform self-checkout by either using a smartphone or putting items into a bin near the register that scans the tags without having to orient each one toward the scanner.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Some stores use RFID-tagged items to trigger systems that provide customers with more information or suggestions, such as fitting rooms at Chanel and the "Color Bar" at Kendra Scott stores.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Item tagging can also provide protection against theft by customers and employees by using electronic article surveillance (EAS).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tags of different types can be physically removed with a special tool or deactivated electronically when payment is made.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] On leaving the shop, customers have to pass near an RFID detector; if they have items with active RFID tags, an alarm sounds, indicating an unpaid-for item.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Casinos can use RFID to authenticate poker chips, and can selectively invalidate any chips known to be stolen.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are widely used in identification badges, replacing earlier magnetic stripe cards.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These badges need only be held within a certain distance of the reader to authenticate the holder.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tags can also be placed on vehicles, which can be read at a distance, to allow entrance to controlled areas without having to stop the vehicle and present a card or enter an access code.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2010, Vail Resorts began using UHF Passive RFID tags in ski passes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Automotive brands have adopted RFID for social media product placement more quickly than other industries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Mercedes was an early adopter in 2011 at the PGA Golf Championships, and a Hyundai stand in the 2013 Geneva Motor Show uses RFID for streamlining social activation marketing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] To prevent retailers diverting products, manufacturers are exploring the use of RFID tags on promoted merchandise so that they can track exactly which product has sold through the supply chain at fully discounted prices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Yard management, shipping and freight and distribution centers use RFID tracking.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In the railroad industry, RFID tags mounted on locomotives and rolling stock identify the owner, identification number and type of equipment and its characteristics.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This can be used with a database to identify the type, origin, destination, etc. of the commodities being carried.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In commercial aviation, RFID is used to support maintenance on commercial aircraft.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A standard for RFID baggage tags has been established by the IATA at the Passenger Services Conference in Geneva of November 2005.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The Las Vegas McCarran International Airport and Hong Kong International Airport were among several airports to have tests conducted, concurring the presence of functional RFID baggage tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Some countries are using RFID for vehicle registration and enforcement.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID can help detect and retrieve stolen cars.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID is used in intelligent transportation systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In New York City, RFID readers are deployed at intersections to track E-ZPass tags as a means for monitoring the traffic flow.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The data is fed through the broadband wireless infrastructure to the traffic management center to be used in adaptive traffic control of the traffic lights.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Where ship, rail, or highway tanks are being loaded, a fixed RFID antenna contained in a transfer hose can read an RFID tag affixed to the tank, positively identifying it.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] At least one company has introduced RFID to identify and locate underground infrastructure assets such as gas pipelines, sewer lines, electrical cables, communication cables, etc.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The first RFID passports ("E-passport") were issued by Malaysia in 1998.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In addition to information also contained on the visual data page of the passport, Malaysian e-passports record the travel history (time, date, and place) of entry into and exit out of the country.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Standards for RFID passports are determined by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), and are contained in ICAO Document 9303, Part 1, Volumes 1 and 2 (6th edition, 2006).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] ICAO refers to the ISO/IEC 14443 RFID chips in e-passports as "contactless integrated circuits".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] ICAO standards provide for e-passports to be identifiable by a standard e-passport logo on the front cover.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since 2006, RFID tags included in new United States passports store the same information that is printed within the passport, and include a digital picture of the owner.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The department will also implement Basic Access Control (BAC), which functions as a personal identification number (PIN) in the form of characters printed on the passport data page.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Before a passport's tag can be read, this PIN must be entered into an RFID reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The BAC also enables the encryption of any communication between the chip and interrogator.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In many countries, RFID tags can be used to pay for mass transit fares on bus, trains, or subways, or to collect tolls on highways.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Some bike lockers are operated with RFID cards assigned to individual users.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A prepaid card is required to open or enter a facility or locker and is used to track and charge based on how long the bike is parked.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The Zipcar car-sharing service uses RFID cards for locking and unlocking cars and for member identification.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In Singapore, RFID replaces paper Season Parking Ticket (SPT).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags for animals represent one of the earliest uses of RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Originally meant for large ranches and rough terrain, since the outbreak of mad-cow disease, RFID has become crucial in animal identification management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An implantable RFID tag or transponder can also be used for animal identification.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The transponders are better known as Passive Integrated Transponder (PIT) tags, passive RFID, or **chips** on animals.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The Canadian Cattle Identification Agency began using RFID tags as a replacement for barcode tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Currently, CCIA tags are used in Wisconsin and by United States farmers on a voluntary basis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The USDA is currently developing its own program.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are required for all cattle sold in Australia and in some states, sheep and goats as well.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Biocompatible microchip implants that use RFID technology are being routinely implanted in humans.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The first-ever human to receive an RFID microchip implant was American artist Eduardo Kac in 1997.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Kac implanted the microchip live on television (and also live on the Internet) in the context of his artwork *Time Capsule*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A year later, British professor of cybernetics Kevin Warwick had an RFID chip implanted in his arm by his general practitioner, George Boulos.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2004, the 'Baja Beach Club' operated by Conrad Chase in Barcelona and Rotterdam offered implanted chips to identify their VIP customers, who could in turn use it to pay for service.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2009, British scientist Mark Gasson had an advanced glass capsule RFID device surgically implanted into his left hand and subsequently demonstrated how a computer virus could wirelessly infect his implant and then be transmitted on to other systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The Food and Drug Administration in the United States approved the use of RFID chips in humans in 2004.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] There is controversy regarding human applications of implantable RFID technology including concerns that individuals could potentially be tracked by carrying an identifier unique to them.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Privacy advocates have protested against implantable RFID chips, warning of potential abuse.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Some are concerned this could lead to abuse by an authoritarian government, to removal of freedoms, and to the emergence of an "ultimate panopticon", a society where all citizens behave in a socially accepted manner because others might be watching.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] On July 22, 2006, Reuters reported that two hackers, Newitz and Westhues, at a conference in New York City demonstrated that they could clone the RFID signal from a human implanted RFID chip, indicating that the device was not as secure as was previously claimed.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The UFO religion Universe People is notorious online for their vocal opposition to human RFID chipping, which they claim is a saurian attempt to enslave the human race; one of their web domains is "dont-get-chipped".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Adoption of RFID in the medical industry has been widespread and very effective.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Hospitals are among the first users to combine both active and passive RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Active tags track high-value, or frequently moved items, and passive tags track smaller, lower cost items that only need room-level identification.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Medical facility rooms can collect data from transmissions of RFID badges worn by patients and employees, as well as from tags assigned to items such as mobile medical devices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) recently announced plans to deploy RFID in hospitals across America to improve care and reduce costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since 2004, a number of U.S. hospitals have begun implanting patients with RFID tags and using RFID systems; the systems are typically used for workflow and inventory management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The use of RFID to prevent mix-ups between sperm and ova in IVF clinics is also being considered.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In October 2004, the FDA approved the USA's first RFID chips that can be implanted in humans.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The 134 kHz RFID chips, from VeriChip Corp. can incorporate personal medical information and could save lives and limit injuries from errors in medical treatments, according to the company.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Anti-RFID activists Katherine Albrecht and Liz McIntyre discovered an FDA Warning Letter that spelled out health risks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Libraries have used RFID to replace the barcodes on library items.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag can contain identifying information or may just be a key into a database.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An RFID system may replace or supplement bar codes and may offer another method of inventory management and self-service checkout by patrons.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It can also act as a security device, taking the place of the more traditional electromagnetic security strip.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It is estimated that over 30 million library items worldwide now contain RFID tags, including some in the Vatican Library in Rome.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since RFID tags can be read through an item, there is no need to open a book cover or DVD case to scan an item, and a stack of books can be read simultaneously.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Book tags can be read while books are in motion on a conveyor belt, which reduces staff time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This can all be done by the borrowers themselves, reducing the need for library staff assistance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] With portable readers, inventories could be done on a whole shelf of materials within seconds.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] However, as of 2008, this technology remained too costly for many smaller libraries, and the conversion period has been estimated at 11 months for an average-size library.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A 2004 Dutch estimate was that a library which lends 100,000 books per year should plan on a cost of €50,000 (borrow- and return-stations: 12,500 each, detection porches 10,000 each; tags 0.36 each).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID taking a large burden off staff could also mean that fewer staff will be needed, resulting in some of them getting laid off, but that has so far not happened in North America where recent surveys have not returned a single library that cut staff because of adding RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In fact, library budgets are being reduced for personnel and increased for infrastructure, making it necessary for libraries to add automation to compensate for the reduced staff size.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Also, the tasks that RFID takes over are largely not the primary tasks of librarians.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A finding in the Netherlands is that borrowers are pleased with the fact that staff are now more available for answering questions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Privacy concerns have been raised surrounding library use of RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Because some RFID tags can be read up to 100 metres (330 ft) away, there is some concern over whether sensitive information could be collected from an unwilling source.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] However, library RFID tags do not contain any patron information, and the tags used in the majority of libraries use a frequency only readable from approximately 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Another concern is that a non-library agency could potentially record the RFID tags of every person leaving the library without the library administrator's knowledge or consent.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] One simple option is to let the book transmit a code that has meaning only in conjunction with the library's database.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Another possible enhancement would be to give each book a new code every time it is returned.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In future, should readers become ubiquitous (and possibly networked), then stolen books could be traced even outside the library.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Tag removal could be made difficult if the tags are so small that they fit invisibly inside a (random) page, possibly put there by the publisher.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID technologies are now also implemented in end-user applications in museums.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] An example was the custom-designed temporary research application, "eXspot", at the Exploratorium, a science museum in San Francisco, California.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A visitor entering the museum received an RF tag that could be carried as a card.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The eXspot system enabled the visitor to receive information about specific exhibits.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Aside from the exhibit information, the visitor could take photographs of themselves at the exhibit.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It was also intended to allow the visitor to take data for later analysis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The collected information could be retrieved at home from a "personalized" website keyed to the RFID tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2004, school authorities in the Japanese city of Osaka made a decision to start chipping children's clothing, backpacks, and student IDs in a primary school.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Later, in 2007, a school in Doncaster, England, piloted a monitoring system designed to keep tabs on pupils by tracking radio chips in their uniforms.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] St Charles Sixth Form College in west London, England, starting in 2008, uses an RFID card system to check in and out of the main gate, to both track attendance and prevent unauthorized entrance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Similarly, Whitcliffe Mount School in Cleckheaton, England, uses RFID to track pupils and staff in and out of the building via a specially designed card.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In the Philippines, during 2012, some schools already use RFID in IDs for borrowing books.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Gates in those particular schools also have RFID scanners for buying items at school shops and canteens.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID is also used in school libraries, and to sign in and out for student and teacher attendance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID for timing races began in the early 1990s with pigeon racing, introduced by the company Deister Electronics in Germany.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID can provide race start and end timings for individuals in large races where it is impossible to get accurate stopwatch readings for every entrant.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In races using RFID, racers wear tags that are read by antennas placed alongside the track or on mats across the track.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] UHF tags provide accurate readings with specially designed antennas.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Rush error, lap count errors and accidents at race start are avoided, as anyone can start and finish at any time without being in a batch mode.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The design of the chip and of the antenna controls the range from which it can be read.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Short range compact chips are twist tied to the shoe, or strapped to the ankle with hook-and-loop fasteners.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The chips must be about 400 mm from the mat, therefore giving very good temporal resolution.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Alternatively, a chip plus a very large (125 mm square) antenna can be incorporated into the bib number worn on the athlete's chest at a height of about 1.25 m (4.1 ft).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Passive and active RFID systems are used in off-road events such as Orienteering, Enduro and Hare and Hounds racing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Riders have a transponder on their person, normally on their arm.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] When they complete a lap they swipe or touch the receiver which is connected to a computer and log their lap time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID is being adapted by many recruitment agencies which have a PET (physical endurance test) as their qualifying procedure, especially in cases where the candidate volumes may run into millions (Indian Railway recruitment cells, police and power sector).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A number of ski resorts have adopted RFID tags to provide skiers hands-free access to ski lifts.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Skiers do not have to take their passes out of their pockets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Ski jackets have a left pocket into which the chip+card fits.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This nearly contacts the sensor unit on the left of the turnstile as the skier pushes through to the lift.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These systems were based on high frequency (HF) at 13.56 MHz.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The bulk of ski areas in Europe, from Verbier to Chamonix, use these systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The NFL in the United States equips players with RFID chips that measures speed, distance and direction traveled by each player in real-time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Currently, cameras stay focused on the quarterback; however, numerous plays are happening simultaneously on the field.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The RFID chip will provide new insight into these simultaneous plays.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The chip triangulates the player's position within six inches and will be used to digitally broadcast replays.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The RFID chip will make individual player information accessible to the public.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The data will be available via the NFL 2015 app.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The RFID chips are manufactured by Zebra Technologies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Zebra Technologies tested the RFID chip in 18 stadiums last year to track vector data.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are not necessarily "superior" to barcodes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are often a complement, but not a substitute, for Universal Product Code (UPC) or European Article Number (EAN) barcodes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] They may never completely replace barcodes, due in part to their higher cost and the advantage of multiple data sources on the same object.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Also, unlike RFID labels, barcodes can be generated and distributed electronically by e-mail or mobile phone, for printing or display by the recipient.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The new EPC, along with several other schemes, is widely available at reasonable cost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The storage of data associated with tracking items will require many terabytes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Filtering and categorizing RFID data is needed to create useful information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It is likely that goods will be tracked by the pallet using RFID tags, and at package level with UPC or EAN from unique barcodes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The unique identity is a mandatory requirement for RFID tags, despite special choice of the numbering scheme.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tag data capacity is large enough that each individual tag will have a unique code, while current barcodes are limited to a single type code for a particular product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The uniqueness of RFID tags means that a product may be tracked as it moves from location to location while being delivered to a person.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This may help to combat theft and other forms of product loss.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tracing of products is an important feature that is well supported with RFID tags containing a unique identity of the tag and the serial number of the object.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This may help companies cope with quality deficiencies and resulting recall campaigns, but also contributes to concern about tracking and profiling of persons after the sale.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Since around 2007, there has been increasing development in the use of RFID in the waste management industry.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID tags are installed on waste collection carts, linking carts to the owner's account for easy billing and service verification.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The tag is embedded into a garbage and recycle container, and the RFID reader is affixed to the garbage and recycle trucks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] RFID also measures a customer's set-out rate and provides insight as to the number of carts serviced by each waste collection vehicle.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This RFID process replaces traditional "pay as you throw" (PAYT) municipal solid waste usage-pricing models.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Active RFID tags have the potential to function as low-cost remote sensors that broadcast telemetry back to a base station.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Applications of tagometry data could include sensing of road conditions by implanted beacons, weather reports, and noise level monitoring.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Passive RFID tags can also report sensor data.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] For example, the Wireless Identification and Sensing Platform is a passive tag that reports temperature, acceleration and capacitance to commercial Gen2 RFID readers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It is possible that active or battery-assisted passive (BAP) RFID tags could broadcast a signal to an in-store receiver to determine whether the RFID tag – and by extension, the product it is attached to – is in the store.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] To avoid injuries to humans and animals, RF transmission needs to be controlled.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] A number of organizations have set standards for RFID, including the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), ASTM International, the DASH7 Alliance and EPCglobal.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Every country can set its own rules for frequency allocation for RFID tags, and not all radio bands are available in all countries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These frequencies are known as the ISM bands (Industrial Scientific and Medical bands).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The return signal of the tag may still cause interference for other radio users.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In North America, UHF can be used unlicensed for 902–928 MHz (±13 MHz from the 915 MHz center frequency), but restrictions exist for transmission power.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In Europe, RFID and other low-power radio applications are regulated by ETSI recommendations EN 300 220 and EN 302 208, and ERO recommendation 70 03, allowing RFID operation with somewhat complex band restrictions from 865–868 MHz.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Readers are required to monitor a channel before transmitting ("Listen Before Talk"); this requirement has led to some restrictions on performance, the resolution of which is a subject of current research.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The North American UHF standard is not accepted in France as it interferes with its military bands.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] On July 25, 2012, Japan changed its UHF band to 920 MHz, more closely matching the United States' 915 MHz band, establishing an international standard environment for RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In some countries, a site license is needed, which needs to be applied for at the local authorities, and can be revoked.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] As of 31 October 2014, regulations are in place in 78 countries representing approximately 96.5% of the world's GDP, and work on regulations was in progress in three countries representing approximately 1% of the world's GDP.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In order to ensure global interoperability of products, several organizations have set up additional standards for RFID testing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These standards include conformance, performance and interoperability tests.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] EPC Gen2 is short for *EPCglobal UHF Class 1 Generation 2*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] EPCglobal, a joint venture between GS1 and GS1 US, is working on international standards for the use of mostly passive RFID and the Electronic Product Code (EPC) in the identification of many items in the supply chain for companies worldwide.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] One of the missions of EPCglobal was to simplify the Babel of protocols prevalent in the RFID world in the 1990s.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] Two tag air interfaces (the protocol for exchanging information between a tag and a reader) were defined (but not ratified) by EPCglobal prior to 2003.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] These protocols, commonly known as Class 0 and Class 1, saw significant commercial implementation in 2002–2005.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2004, the Hardware Action Group created a new protocol, the Class 1 Generation 2 interface, which addressed a number of problems that had been experienced with Class 0 and Class 1 tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The EPC Gen2 standard was approved in December 2004.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] This was approved after a contention from Intermec that the standard may infringe a number of their RFID-related patents.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] It was decided that the standard itself does not infringe their patents, making the standard royalty free.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The EPC Gen2 standard was adopted with minor modifications as ISO 18000-6C in 2006.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The updated Class 1 Generation 2 version 3.0 standard was ratified in January 2024.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] The new standard includes a longer power-up period (2500 microseconds instead of 1500), and the option to reduce power slightly during a command, in order to reduce the chances of partial responses from tags at the edge of the read zone.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] New commands QueryX and QueryY, combining Select and Query, have been added, in addition to various other minor changes and additions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p01] In 2007, the lowest cost of Gen2 EPC inlay was offered by the now-defunct company SmartCode, at a price of $0.05 apiece in volumes of 100 million or more.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Life-cycle studies report that per-tag climate impacts can vary with tag design and system boundaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] In the United States, e-waste regulation is comparatively fragmented: the EPA notes that 25 states plus the District of Columbia have electronics recycling laws.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Mitigation approaches discussed in the literature include eco-design, take-back/reuse schemes, and substitution with chipless RFID where feasible (tags “not equipped with” an ASIC), though chipless approaches have technical performance trade-offs and infrastructure constraints.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Research using RFID readers and tag detections has also been used to derive “co-presence” networks (co-location inferred from which readers detect which tags), illustrating how RFID-derived co-location patterns can be analyzed.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Not every successful reading of a tag (an observation) is useful for business purposes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] A large amount of data may be generated that is not useful for managing inventory or other applications.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] For example, a customer moving a product from one shelf to another, or a pallet load of articles that passes several readers while being moved in a warehouse, are events that do not produce data that are meaningful to an inventory control system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Event filtering is required to reduce this data inflow to a meaningful depiction of moving goods passing a threshold.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Various concepts have been designed, mainly offered as *middleware* performing the filtering from noisy and redundant raw data to significant processed data.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The frequencies used for UHF RFID in the USA are as of 2007 incompatible with those of Europe or Japan.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Furthermore, no emerging standard has yet become as universal as the barcode.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] To address international trade concerns, it is necessary to use a tag that is operational within all of the international frequency domains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] A primary RFID security concern is the illicit tracking of RFID tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Tags, which are world-readable, pose a risk to both personal location privacy and corporate/military security.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Such concerns have been raised with respect to the United States Department of Defense's adoption of RFID tags for supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] More generally, privacy organizations have expressed concerns in the context of ongoing efforts to embed electronic product code (EPC) RFID tags in general-use products.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This is mostly as a result of the fact that RFID tags can be read, and legitimate transactions with readers can be eavesdropped on, from non-trivial distances.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] RFID used in access control, payment and eID (e-passport) systems operate at a shorter range than EPC RFID systems but are also vulnerable to skimming and eavesdropping, albeit at shorter distances.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] A second method of prevention is by using cryptography.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Rolling codes and challenge–response authentication (CRA) are commonly used to foil monitor-repetition of the messages between the tag and reader, as any messages that have been recorded would prove to be unsuccessful on repeat transmission.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Rolling codes rely upon the tag's ID being changed after each interrogation, while CRA uses software to ask for a cryptographically coded response from the tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The protocols used during CRA can be symmetric, or may use public key cryptography.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] While a variety of secure protocols have been suggested for RFID tags, in order to support long read range at low cost, many RFID tags have barely enough power available to support very low-power and therefore simple security protocols such as cover-coding.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Unauthorized reading of RFID tags presents a risk to privacy and to business secrecy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Unauthorized readers can potentially use RFID information to identify or track packages, persons, carriers, or the contents of a package.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Several prototype systems are being developed to combat unauthorized reading, including RFID signal interruption, as well as the possibility of legislation, and 700 scientific papers have been published on this matter since 2002.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] There are also concerns that the database structure of Object Naming Service may be susceptible to infiltration, similar to denial-of-service attacks, after the EPCglobal Network ONS root servers were shown to be vulnerable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Microchip-induced tumors have been noted during animal trials.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] In an effort to prevent the passive "skimming" of RFID-enabled cards or passports, the U.S.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] General Services Administration (GSA) issued a set of test procedures for evaluating electromagnetically opaque sleeves.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] For shielding products to be in compliance with FIPS-201 guidelines, they must meet or exceed this published standard; compliant products are listed on the website of the U.S.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The United States government requires that when new ID cards are issued, they must be delivered with an approved shielding sleeve or holder.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Although many wallets and passport holders are advertised to protect personal information, there is little evidence that RFID skimming is a serious threat; data encryption and use of EMV chips rather than RFID makes this sort of theft rare.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] There are contradictory opinions as to whether aluminum can prevent reading of RFID chips.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Some people claim that aluminum shielding, essentially creating a Faraday cage, does work.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Others claim that simply wrapping an RFID card in aluminum foil only makes transmission more difficult and is not completely effective at preventing it.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Shielding effectiveness depends on the frequency being used.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Low-frequency LowFID tags, like those used in implantable devices for humans and pets, are relatively resistant to shielding, although thick metal foil will prevent most reads.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] High frequency HighFID tags (13.56 MHz—smart cards and access badges) are sensitive to shielding and are difficult to read when within a few centimetres of a metal surface.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The use of RFID has engendered considerable controversy and some consumer privacy advocates have initiated product boycotts.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Consumer privacy experts Katherine Albrecht and Liz McIntyre are two prominent critics of the "spychip" technology.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Most concerns revolve around the fact that RFID tags affixed to products remain functional even after the products have been purchased and taken home; thus, they may be used for surveillance and other purposes unrelated to their supply chain inventory functions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The RFID Network responded to these fears in the first episode of their syndicated cable TV series, saying that they are unfounded, and let RF engineers demonstrate how RFID works.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] They provided images of RF engineers driving an RFID-enabled van around a building and trying to take an inventory of items inside.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] They also discussed satellite tracking of a passive RFID tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The concerns raised may be addressed in part by use of the Clipped Tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The Clipped Tag is an RFID tag designed to increase privacy for the purchaser of an item.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The Clipped Tag has been suggested by IBM researchers Paul Moskowitz and Guenter Karjoth.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] After the point of sale, a person may tear off a portion of the tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This allows the transformation of a long-range tag into a proximity tag that still may be read, but only at short range – less than a few inches or centimeters.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The modification of the tag may be confirmed visually.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The tag may still be used later for returns, recalls, or recycling.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] However, read range is a function of both the reader and the tag itself.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Improvements in technology may increase read ranges for tags.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Tags may be read at longer ranges than they are designed for by increasing reader power.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The limit on read distance then becomes the signal-to-noise ratio of the signal reflected from the tag back to the reader.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Researchers at two security conferences have demonstrated that passive Ultra-HighFID tags normally read at ranges of up to 30 feet can be read at ranges of 50 to 69 feet using suitable equipment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] In January 2004, privacy advocates from CASPIAN and the German privacy group FoeBuD were invited to the METRO Future Store in Germany, where an RFID pilot project was implemented.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] It was uncovered by accident that METRO "Payback" customer loyalty cards contained RFID tags with customer IDs, a fact that was disclosed neither to customers receiving the cards, nor to this group of privacy advocates.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This happened despite assurances by METRO that no customer identification data was tracked and all RFID usage was clearly disclosed.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] During the UN World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS) in November 2005, Richard Stallman, the founder of the free software movement, protested the use of RFID security cards by covering his card with aluminum foil.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] In 2004–2005, the Federal Trade Commission staff conducted a workshop and review of RFID privacy concerns and issued a report recommending best practices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] RFID was one of the main topics of the 2006 Chaos Communication Congress (organized by the Chaos Computer Club in Berlin) and triggered a large press debate.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Topics included electronic passports, Mifare cryptography and the tickets for the FIFA World Cup 2006.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Talks showed how the first real-world mass application of RFID at the 2006 FIFA Football World Cup worked.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] The group monochrom staged a "Hack RFID" song.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Some individuals have grown to fear the loss of rights due to RFID human implantation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] By early 2007, Chris Paget of San Francisco, California, showed that RFID information could be pulled from a US passport card by using only $250 worth of equipment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This suggests that with the information captured, it would be possible to clone such cards.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] According to ZDNet, critics believe that RFID will lead to tracking individuals' every movement and will be an invasion of privacy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] In the book *SpyChips: How Major Corporations and Government Plan to Track Your Every Move* by Katherine Albrecht and Liz McIntyre, one is encouraged to "imagine a world of no privacy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Where your every purchase is monitored and recorded in a database and your every belonging is numbered.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Where someone many states away or perhaps in another country has a record of everything you have ever bought.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] What's more, they can be tracked and monitored remotely".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This simple method cannot safely be used to deactivate RFID features in electronic devices, or those implanted in living tissue, because of the risk of damage to the "host".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] However the time required is extremely short (a second or two of radiation) and the method works in many other non-electronic and inanimate items, long before heat or fire become of concern.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Some RFID tags implement a "kill command" mechanism to permanently and irreversibly disable them.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] This mechanism can be applied if the chip itself is trusted or the mechanism is known by the person that wants to "kill" the tag.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] UHF RFID tags that comply with the EPC2 Gen 2 Class 1 standard usually support this mechanism, while protecting the chip from being killed with a password.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/radio-frequency-identification-p02] Guessing or cracking this needed 32-bit password for killing a tag would not be difficult for a determined attacker.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In commerce, **supply chain management** (**SCM**) deals with a system of procurement (purchasing raw materials/components), operations management, logistics and marketing channels, through which raw materials can be developed into finished products and delivered to their end customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This can include the movement and storage of raw materials, work-in-process inventory, finished goods, and end-to-end order fulfilment from the point of origin to the point of consumption.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Interconnected, interrelated or interlinked networks, channels and node businesses combine in the provision of products and services required by end customers in a supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM is the broad range of activities required to plan, control and execute a product's flow from materials to production to distribution in the most economical way possible.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM encompasses the integrated planning and execution of processes required to optimize the flow of materials, information and capital in functions that broadly include demand planning, sourcing, production, inventory management and logistics—or storage and transportation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management strives for an integrated, multidisciplinary, multi-method approach.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Research in supply chain management focuses on topics such as resilience, sustainability, and risk management, among others.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Some suggest that the "people dimension" of SCM, ethical issues, internal integration, transparency/visibility, and human capital or talent management are topics that have been underrepresented on the research agenda.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management, techniques with the aim of coordinating all parts of SC, from supplying raw materials to delivering and/or resumption of products, tries to minimize total costs with respect to existing conflicts among the chain partners.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] An example of these conflicts is the interrelation between the sale department desiring to have higher inventory levels to fulfill demands and the warehouse for which lower inventories are desired to reduce holding costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In 1982, Keith Oliver, a consultant at Booz Allen Hamilton, introduced the term "supply chain management" to the public domain in an interview for the Financial Times.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In the mid-1990s, the term "supply chain management" gained popularity when a flurry of articles and books came out on the subject.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chains were originally defined as encompassing all activities associated with the flow and transformation of goods from raw materials through to the end user or final consumer, as well as the associated information flows.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Mentzer *et al.* consider it worthy of note that the final consumer was included within these early definitions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management was then further defined as the integration of supply chain activities through improved supply chain relationships to achieve a competitive advantage.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In the late 1990s, "supply chain management" (SCM) rose to prominence, and operations managers began to use it in their titles with increasing regularity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A supply chain, as opposed to supply chain management, is a set of firms who move materials "forward", or a set of organizations, directly linked by one or more upstream and downstream flows of products, services, finances, or information from a source to a customer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is the management of such a chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Mentzer *et al.* make a further distinction between "supply chain management" and a "supply chain orientation".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The latter term involves a recognition that a business strategy cannot be fulfilled without managing the activities of suppliers and customers upstream and downstream, whereas the former term is used for "the actual implementation of this orientation".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management software includes tools or modules used to execute supply chain transactions, manage supplier relationships, and control associated business processes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The overall goal of the software is to improve supply chain performance by monitoring a company's supply chain network from end-to-end (suppliers, transporters, returns, warehouses, retailers, manufacturers, and customers).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In some cases, a supply chain includes the collection of goods after consumer use for recycling or the reverse logistics processes for returning faulty or unwanted products back to producers up the value chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is a cross-functional approach that includes managing the movement of raw materials into an organization, certain aspects of the internal processing of materials into finished goods, and the movement of finished goods out of the organization and toward the end consumer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] As organizations strive to focus on core competencies and become more flexible, they reduce ownership of raw materials sources and distribution channels.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] These functions are increasingly being outsourced to other firms that can perform the activities better or more cost effectively.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The effect is to increase the number of organizations involved in satisfying customer demand, while reducing managerial control of daily logistics operations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Less control and more supply chain partners lead to the creation of the concept of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is concerned with improving trust and collaboration among supply chain partners, thus improving inventory visibility and the velocity of inventory movement.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Organizations increasingly find that they must rely on effective supply chains, or networks, to compete in the global market and networked economy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In Peter Drucker's (1998) new management paradigms, this concept of business relationships extends beyond traditional enterprise boundaries and seeks to organize entire business processes throughout a value chain of multiple companies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In recent decades, globalization, outsourcing, and information technology have enabled many organizations, such as Dell and Hewlett-Packard, to successfully operate collaborative supply networks in which each specialized business partner focuses on only a few key strategic activities.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This inter-organizational supply network can be acknowledged as a new form of organization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] However, with the complicated interactions among the players, the network structure fits neither "market" nor "hierarchy" categories.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] It is not clear what kind of performance impacts different supply-network structures could have on firms, and little is known about the coordination conditions and trade-offs that may exist among the players.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] From a systems perspective, a complex network structure can be decomposed into individual component firms.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Traditionally, companies in a supply network concentrate on the inputs and outputs of the processes, with little concern for the internal management working of other individual players.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Therefore, the choice of an internal management control structure is known to impact local firm performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In the 21st century, changes in the business environment have contributed to the development of supply chain networks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] First, as an outcome of globalization and the proliferation of multinational companies, joint ventures, strategic alliances, and business partnerships, significant success factors were identified, complementing the earlier "just-in-time", lean manufacturing, and agile manufacturing practices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Second, technological changes, particularly the dramatic fall in communication costs (a significant component of transaction costs), have led to changes in coordination among the members of the supply chain network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Many researchers have recognized supply network structures as a new organizational form, using terms such as "Keiretsu", "Extended Enterprise", "virtual supply chain", "Global Production Network", and "Next Generation Manufacturing System".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In general, such a structure can be defined as "a group of semi-independent organizations, each with their capabilities, which collaborate in ever-changing constellations to serve one or more markets in order to achieve some business goal specific to that collaboration".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is also important for organizational learning.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Firms with geographically more extensive supply chains connecting diverse trading cliques tend to become more innovative and productive.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The security-management system for supply chains is described in ISO/IEC 28000 and ISO/IEC 28001 and related standards published jointly by the ISO and the IEC.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply Chain Management draws heavily from the areas of operations management, logistics, procurement, and information technology, and strives for an integrated approach.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The importance of supply chain management proved crucial in the 2019-2020 fight against the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic that swept across the world.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] During the pandemic period, governments in countries which had in place effective domestic supply chain management had enough medical supplies to support their needs and enough to donate their surplus to front-line health workers in other jurisdictions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The devastating COVID-19 crisis in US has turned many sectors of the local economy upside down, including the country's storied logistics industry.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Some organizations were able to quickly develop foreign supply chains in order to import much needed medical supplies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Cross-border supply chains can increase political risk.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] An important element of SCM is supply chain resilience, defined as "the capacity of a supply chain to persist, adapt, or transform in the face of change".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] For a long time, the interpretation of resilience in the sense of engineering resilience (= robustness) prevailed in supply chain management, leading to the notion of *persistence*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A popular implementation of this idea is given by measuring the *time-to-survive* and the *time-to-recover* of the supply chain, allowing to identify weak points in the system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The APICS Certified Supply Chain Professional (CSCP) program emphasizes the importance of managing risks and enhancing resilience.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] According to APICS, in order to manage global interruptions and preserve operational continuity, a robust supply chain is vital.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] More recently, the interpretations of resilience in the sense of ecological resilience and social–ecological resilience have led to the notions of *adaptation* and *transformation*, respectively.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In a simple form, ecological resilience represents the capacity of a system to absorb disturbances and survive despite these changes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The ecological resilience is different from conditions far from equilibrium steady states, where disturbances and instabilities may shift a system into a different regime of behavior or stability domain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This leads to a panarchical interpretation of a supply chain, embedding it into a system of systems, allowing to analyze the interactions of the supply chain with systems that operate at other levels (e.g. society, political economy, planet Earth).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] For example, these three components of resilience can be discussed for the 2021 Suez Canal obstruction, when a ship blocked the canal for several days.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Persistence means to "bounce back"; in our example it is about removing the ship as quickly as possible to allow "normal" operations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Adaptation means to accept that the system has reached a "new normal" state and to act accordingly; here, this can be implemented by redirecting ships around the African cape or use alternative modes of transport.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Finally, transformation means to question the assumptions of globalization, outsourcing and linear supply chains and to envision alternatives; in this example this could lead to local and circular supply chains that do not need global transportation routes any longer.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Public policy can increase the resilience of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Six major movements can be observed in the evolution of supply chain management studies: creation, integration, globalization, specialization phases one and two, and SCM 2.0.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The term "supply chain management" was first coined by Keith Oliver in 1982.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the concept of a supply chain in management was of great importance long before, in the early 20th century, especially with the creation of the assembly line.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The characteristics of this era of supply chain management include the need for large-scale changes, re-engineering, downsizing driven by cost reduction programs, and widespread attention to Japanese management practices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the term became widely adopted after the publication of the seminal book *Introduction to Supply Chain Management* in 1999 by Robert B.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Nichols, Jr., which published over 25,000 copies and was translated into Japanese, Korean, Chinese, and Russian.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This era of supply chain management studies was highlighted with the development of electronic data interchange (EDI) systems in the 1960s and developed through the 1990s by the introduction of enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This era has continued to develop into the 21st century with the expansion of Internet-based collaborative systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This era of supply chain evolution is characterized by both increasing value-added and reducing costs through integration.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A supply chain can be classified as a stage 1, 2, or 3 network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In stage 1–type supply chain, systems such as production, storage, distribution, and material control are not linked and are independent of each other.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In a stage 2 supply chain, these are integrated under one plan, and enterprise resource planning (ERP) is enabled.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A stage 3 supply chain is one that achieves vertical integration with upstream suppliers and downstream customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] An example of this kind of supply chain is Tesco.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] It is the third movement of supply chain management development, the globalization era, can be characterized by the attention given to global systems of supplier relationships and the expansion of supply chains beyond national boundaries and into other continents.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Although the use of global sources in organizations' supply chains can be traced back several decades (e.g., in the oil industry), it was not until the late 1980s that a considerable number of organizations started to integrate global sources into their core business.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This era is characterized by the globalization of supply chain management in organizations with the goal of increasing their competitive advantage, adding value, and reducing costs through global sourcing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In the 1990s, companies began to focus on "core competencies" and specialization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] They abandoned vertical integration, sold off non-core operations, and outsourced those functions to other companies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This changed management requirements, as the supply chain extended beyond the company walls and management was distributed across specialized supply chain partnerships.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This transition also refocused the fundamental perspectives of each organization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) became brand owners that required visibility deep into their supply base.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] They had to control the entire supply chain from above, instead of from within.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Contract manufacturers had to manage bills of material with different part-numbering schemes from multiple OEMs and support customer requests for work-in-process visibility and vendor-managed inventory (VMI).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The specialization model creates manufacturing and distribution networks composed of several individual supply chains specific to producers, suppliers, and customers that work together to design, manufacture, distribute, market, sell, and service a product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This set of partners may change according to a given market, region, or channel, resulting in a proliferation of trading partner environments, each with its own unique characteristics and demands.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Market forces sometimes demand rapid changes from suppliers, logistics providers, locations, or customers in their role as components of supply chain networks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Outsourced technology hosting for supply chain solutions debuted in the late 1990s and has taken root primarily in transportation and collaboration categories.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This has progressed from the application service provider (ASP) model from roughly 1998 through 2003 to the on-demand model from approximately 2003 through 2006, to the software as a service (SaaS) model currently in focus today.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The term SCM 2.0 has been coined to describe both changes within supply chains themselves as well as the evolution of processes, methods, and tools to manage them in a new era of globalization and specialization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] One element of this is the growing popularity of supply chain collaboration platforms that connect multiple buyers and suppliers with financial institutions, enabling them to conduct automated supply chain finance transactions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Web 2.0 is a trend in the use of the World Wide Web that is meant to increase creativity, information sharing, and collaboration among users.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] At its core, the common attribute of Web 2.0 is to help navigate the vast information available on the Web in order to find what is being bought.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM 2.0 replicates this notion in supply chain operations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Increasing volatility has characterized supply chains since about 2000.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM components are the third element of the four-square circulation framework.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The level of integration and management of a business process link is a function of the number and level of components added to the link.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Consequently, adding more management components or increasing the level of each component can increase the level of integration of the business process link.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Literature on business process reengineering, buyer-supplier relationships, and SCM suggests various possible components that should receive managerial attention when managing supply relationships.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Bowersox and Closs (1996) state that the emphasis on cooperation represents the synergism leading to the highest level of joint achievement.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A primary-level channel participant is a business that is willing to participate in responsibility for inventory ownership or assume other financial risks, thus including primary level components.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A secondary-level participant (specialized) is a business that participates in channel relationships by performing essential services for primary participants, including secondary level components, which support primary participants.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Third-level channel participants and components that support primary-level channel participants and are the fundamental branches of secondary-level components may also be included.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Andrew Cox, Joe Sanderson and Glyn Watson argue that the power resources of buyers and suppliers should be analyzed in order to understand how a supply chain relationship operates.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In some cases, a purchasing firm may exercise more power over its suppliers, in other cases, suppliers may have more power; yet again there will be cases where buyers and suppliers may be interdependent or may have no real power over each other.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Cox, Sanderson and Watson have written extensively on the operation of power regimes within a supply chain context; they have described their work for themselves as "a new perspective on managing in supply chains and networks".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Other studies of power in supply chain relationships have looked at drivers impacting on the potential integration of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Benton in 1998 looked at whether potential asymmetries in inter-firm power within a supply chain could prevent the implementation of effective supply chain execution.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Maloni and Benton note that until their research, "little power research" had been presented in the supply chain literature.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Using French and Raven's typology of the sources of power in the context of the automotive industry, they aimed to analyse the effects of distinct power strategies on relationships between buyers and sellers, and upon supply chain performance and satisfaction.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] They concluded that "prudent use of power" can be beneficial for both the power source and the power target.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Reverse logistics is the process of managing the return of goods and may be considered as an aspect of "aftermarket customer services".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Any time money is taken from a company's warranty reserve or service logistics budget, one can speak of a reverse logistics operation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Reverse logistics also includes the process of managing the return of goods from store, which the returned goods are sent back to warehouse and after that either warehouse scrap the goods or send them back to supplier for replacement depending on the warranty of the merchandise.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Successful SCM requires a change from managing individual functions to integrating activities into key supply chain processes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In an example scenario, a purchasing department places orders as its requirements become known.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The marketing department, responding to customer demand, communicates with several distributors and retailers as it attempts to determine ways to satisfy this demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Information shared between supply chain partners can only be fully leveraged through business process integration, e.g., using electronic data interchange.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain business process integration involves collaborative work between buyers and suppliers, joint product development, common systems, and shared information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] According to Lambert and Cooper (2000), operating an integrated supply chain requires a continuous information flow.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] However, in many companies, management has concluded that optimizing product flows cannot be accomplished without implementing a process approach.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Much has been written about demand management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Customer relationship management concerns the relationship between an organization and its customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] It also provides the customer with real-time information on scheduling and product availability through interfaces with the company's production and distribution operations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Effective business process integration in supply chain management requires not only continuous communication, but also strategic coordination across departments and partner companies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The main reason for this is that it can effectively improve agility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] At the same time, this integration can help businesses respond quickly to changes in demand and improve customer satisfaction.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Inventory management is concerned with ensuring the right stock at the right levels, in the right place, at the right time and the right cost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Inventory management entails inventory planning and forecasting: forecasting helps planning inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Strategic plans are drawn up with suppliers to support the manufacturing flow management process and the development of new products.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In firms whose operations extend globally, sourcing may be managed on a global basis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The desired outcome is a relationship where both parties benefit and a reduction in the time required for the product's design and development.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] (EDI) and internet linkage, to convey possible requirements more rapidly.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] , many of which include the responsibility to coordinate with suppliers on matters of scheduling, supply continuity (inventory), hedging, and research into new sources or programs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Procurement has recently been recognized as a core source of value, driven largely by the increasing trends to outsource products and services, and the changes in the global ecosystem requiring stronger relationships between buyers and sellers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Here, customers and suppliers must be integrated into the product development process in order to reduce the time to market.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] shorten, the appropriate products must be developed and successfully launched with ever-shorter time schedules in order for firms to remain competitive.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] 3. develop production technology in manufacturing flow to manufacture and integrate into the best supply chain flow for the given combination of product and markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Integration of suppliers into the new product development process was shown to have a major impact on product target cost, quality, delivery, and market share.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Tapping into suppliers as a source of innovation requires an extensive process characterized by development of technology sharing, but also involves managing intellectual property issues.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The manufacturing process produces and supplies products to the distribution channels based on past forecasts.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Orders are processes operating on a just-in-time (JIT) basis in minimum lot sizes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Changes in the manufacturing flow process lead to shorter cycle times (cycle time compression), meaning improved responsiveness and efficiency in meeting customer demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] La Londe and Masters found in 1994 research that improved supply chain management and cycle time compression were complementary strategies adopted by forward-looking businesses in the United States.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This concerns the movement of a finished product or service to customers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] In physical distribution, the customer is the final destination of a marketing channel, and the availability of the product or service is a vital part of each channel participant's marketing effort.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] It is also through the physical distribution process that the time and space of customer service become an integral part of marketing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Thus it links a marketing channel with its customers (i.e., it links manufacturers, wholesalers, and retailers).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] is the function within supply chain management that is responsible for overseeing a company's fleet of vehicles.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This includes not only trucks and vans but also other assets like ships, planes, and specialized machinery.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Modern **fleet management** is a key component of **fleet digitalization**.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] It relies heavily on **telematics** and **vehicle tracking systems** to provide real-time data on vehicle location, driver behavior, and engine diagnostics.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This **telemetry** data is used to optimize routes, schedule predictive maintenance, and enhance the overall visibility and control of the physical distribution network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This includes not just the outsourcing of the procurement of materials and components, but also the outsourcing of services that traditionally have been provided in-house.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The logic of this trend is that the company will increasingly focus on those activities in the value chain in which it has a distinctive advantage and outsource everything else.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] This movement has been particularly evident in logistics, where the provision of transport, storage, and inventory control is increasingly subcontracted to specialists or logistics partners.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Also, managing and controlling this network of partners and suppliers requires a blend of central and local involvement: strategic decisions are taken centrally, while the monitoring and control of supplier performance and day-to-day liaison with logistics partners are best managed locally.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Experts found a strong relationship from the largest arcs of supplier and customer integration to market share and profitability.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Taking advantage of supplier capabilities and emphasizing a long-term supply chain perspective in customer relationships can both be correlated with a firm's performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] As logistics competency becomes a critical factor in creating and maintaining competitive advantage, measuring logistics performance becomes increasingly important, because the difference between profitable and unprofitable operations becomes narrower.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] (1985) noted that firms engaging in comprehensive performance measurement realized improvements in overall productivity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] internal measures are generally collected and analyzed by the firm, including cost, customer service, productivity, asset measurement, and quality.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] To reduce a company's cost and expenses, warehousing management is concerned with storage, reducing manpower cost, dispatching authority with on time delivery, loading and unloading facilities with proper area, inventory management system etc.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] There are gaps in the literature on supply chain management studies at present.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] A few authors, such as Halldorsson et al., Ketchen and Hult (2006), and Lavassani et al.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the unit of analysis of most of these theories is not the supply chain but rather another system, such as the firm or the supplier-buyer relationship.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Among the few exceptions is the relational view, which outlines a theory for considering dyads and networks of firms as a key unit of analysis for explaining superior individual firm performance (Dyer and Singh, 1998).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The management of supply chains involve a number of specific challenges regarding the organization of relationships among the different partners along the value chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Formal and informal governance mechanisms are central elements in the management of supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] Particular combinations of governance mechanisms may impact the relational dynamics within the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p01] The need for interdisciplinarity in SCM research has been pointed out by academics in the field.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the study of supply chain management, the concept of centroids has become a useful economic consideration.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In mathematics and physics, a centroid is the arithmetic mean position of all the points in a plane figure.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] For supply chain management, a centroid is a location with a high proportion of a country's population and a high proportion of its manufacturing, generally within 500 mi (805 km).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the US, two major supply chain centroids have been defined, one near Dayton, Ohio, and a second near Riverside, California.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The centroid near Dayton is particularly important because it is closest to the population center of the US and Canada.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Dayton is within 500 miles of 60% of the US population and manufacturing capacity, as well as 60% of Canada's population.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The region includes the interchange between I-70 and I-75, one of the busiest in the nation, with 154,000 vehicles passing through per day, of which 30–35% are trucks hauling goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition, the I-75 corridor is home to the busiest north–south rail route east of the Mississippi River.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] A supply chain is the network of all the individuals, organizations, resources, activities and technology involved in the creation and sale of a product.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] A supply chain encompasses everything from the delivery of source materials from the supplier to the manufacturer through to its eventual delivery to the end user.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The supply chain segment involved with getting the finished product from the manufacturer to the consumer is known as the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In 2010, Wal-Mart announced a big change in its sourcing strategy.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Initially, Wal-Mart relied on intermediaries in the sourcing process.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] It bought only 20% of its stock directly, but the rest were bought through the intermediaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Therefore, the company came to realize that the presence of many intermediaries in the product sourcing was actually increasing the costs in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] To cut these costs, Wal-Mart decided to do away with intermediaries in the supply chain and started direct sourcing of its goods from the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Eduardo Castro-Wright, the then Vice President of Wal-Mart, set an ambitious goal of buying 80% of all Wal-Mart goods directly from the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Walmart started purchasing fruits and vegetables on a global scale, where it interacted directly with the suppliers of these goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The company later engaged the suppliers of other goods, such as cloth and home electronics appliances, directly and eliminated the importing agents.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The purchaser, in this case Wal-Mart, can easily direct the suppliers on how to manufacture certain products so that they can be acceptable to the consumers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, Wal-Mart, through direct sourcing, manages to get the exact product quality as it expects, since it engages the suppliers in the producing of these products, hence quality consistency.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Using agents in the sourcing process in most cases lead to inconsistency in the quality of the products, since the agent's source the products from different manufacturers that have varying qualities.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart managed to source directly 80% profit its stock; this has greatly eliminated the intermediaries and cut down the costs between 5-15%, as markups that are introduced by these middlemen in the supply chain are cut.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] This strategy of direct sourcing not only helped Wal-Mart in reducing the costs in the supply chain but also helped in the improvement of supply chain activities through boosting efficiency throughout the entire process.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In other words, direct sourcing reduced the time that takes the company to source and stocks the products in its stock.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The presence of the intermediaries elongated the time in the process of procurement, which sometimes led to delays in the supply of the commodities in the stores, thus, customers finding empty shelves.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart adopted this strategy of sourcing through centralizing the entire process of procurement and sourcing by setting up four global merchandising points for general goods and clothing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The company instructed all the suppliers to bring their products to these central points that are located in different markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The procurement team assesses the quality brought by the suppliers, buys the goods, and distributes them to various regional markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The procurement and sourcing at centralized places helped the company to consolidate the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The company has established four centralized points, including an office in Mexico City and Canada.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Just a mere piloting test on combining the purchase of fresh apples across the United States, Mexico, and Canada led to the savings of about 10%.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] As a result, the company intended to increase centralization of its procurement in North America for all its fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Strategic vendor partnerships is another strategy the company is using in the sourcing process.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart realized that in order for it to ensure consistency in the quality of the products it offers to the consumers and also maintain a steady supply of goods in its stores at a lower cost, it had to create strategic vendor partnerships with the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart identified and selected the suppliers who met its demand and at the same time offered it the best prices for the goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] It then made a strategic relationship with these vendors by offering and assuring the long-term and high volume of purchases in exchange for the lowest possible prices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, the company has managed to source its products from same suppliers as bulks, but at lower prices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] This enables the company to offer competitive prices for its products in its stores, hence, maintaining a competitive advantage over its competitors whose goods are a more expensive in comparison.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Another sourcing strategy Wal-Mart uses is implementing efficient communication relationships with the vendor networks; this is necessary to improve the material flow.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The company has all the contacts with the suppliers whom they communicate regularly and make dates on when the goods would be needed, so that the suppliers get ready to deliver the goods in time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The efficient communication between the company's procurement team and the inventory management team enables the company to source goods and fill its shelves on time, without causing delays and empty shelves.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In other words, the company realized that in ensuring a steady flow of the goods into the store, the suppliers have to be informed early enough, so that they can act accordingly to avoid delays in the delivery of goods.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, efficient communication is another tool which Wal-Mart is using to make the supply chain be more efficient and to cut costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking is another strategy that Wal-Mart is using to cut costs in its supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking is the process of transferring goods directly from inbound trucks to outbound trucks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] When the trucks from the suppliers arrive at the distribution centers, most of the trucks are not offloaded to keep the goods in the distribution centers or warehouses; they are transferred directly to another truck designated to deliver goods to specific retail stores for sale.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking helps in saving the storage costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Initially, the company was incurring considerable costs of storing the goods from the suppliers in its warehouses and the distributions centers to await the distribution trucks to the retail stores in various regions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Tax-efficient supply chain management is a business model that considers the effect of tax in the design and implementation of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] As the consequence of globalization, cross-national businesses pay different tax rates in different countries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Due to these differences, they may legally optimize their supply chain and increase profits based on tax efficiency.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain networks are integral to an economy, but their health is dependent on the well-being of the environment and society.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain sustainability is a business issue affecting an organization's supply chain or logistics network, and is frequently quantified by comparison with SECH ratings, which address social, ethical, cultural, and health footprints.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] These build on the triple bottom line incorporating economic, social, and environmental aspects.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The more commonly used ESG terminology represents Environment, Social and Governance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Because supply chains may account for over 75% of a company's carbon footprint, many organizations are exploring ways to reduce this and thus improve their profile.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] For example, in July 2009, Wal-Mart announced its intentions to create a global sustainability index that would rate products according to the environmental and social impacts of their manufacturing and distribution.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The index is intended to create environmental accountability in Wal-Mart's supply chain and to provide motivation and infrastructure for other retail companies to do the same.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] It has been reported that companies are increasingly taking environmental performance into account when selecting suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] A 2011 survey by the Carbon Trust found that 50% of multinationals expect to select their suppliers based upon carbon performance in the future and 29% of suppliers could lose their places on 'green supply chains' if they do not have adequate performance records on carbon.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition to environmental concerns, increased globalization within global supply chains challenges human rights and worker exploitation risks within multinational corporations including forced labor and modern slavery.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Textiles, agriculture, and manufacturing are some of the industries with significant labor exploitation risks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] There are many different methods governments, corporations, and NGOs use to prevent labor exploitation, including corporate social responsibility, export controls, import bans, and monitoring labor standards.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The US Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, signed into law by President Obama in July 2010, contained a supply chain sustainability provision in the form of the Conflict Minerals law.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The chain of suppliers and vendors to these reporting companies will be expected to provide appropriate supporting information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Incidents like the 2013 Savar building collapse, with more than 1,100 victims, have led to widespread discussions about corporate social responsibility across global supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Wieland and Handfield (2013) suggest that companies need to audit products and suppliers and that supplier auditing needs to go beyond direct relationships with first-tier suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] They also demonstrate that visibility needs to be improved if supply cannot be directly controlled and that smart and electronic technologies play a key role to improve visibility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Finally, they highlight that collaboration with local partners, across the industry and with universities is crucial to successfully managing social responsibility in supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Recent research proposes a two-phase approach for auditing multitier supply networks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Under this strategy, buyers first audit and drop noncompliant suppliers and then proceed to audit and rectify the remaining ones; when auditing an upper tier, the approach recommends selecting the "least valuable unaudited supplier" as the next candidate for auditing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Geissdoerfer *et al*. suggest that circular supply chain management "remains a rather unexplored area of research".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Although it has the same goals as supply chain engineering, supply chain management is focused on a more traditional management and business based approach, whereas supply chain engineering is focused on a mathematical model based one.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Consultancies and media expect the performance efficacy of digitizing supply chains to be high.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Additive manufacturing and blockchain technology have emerged as the two technologies with some of the highest economic relevance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The potential of additive manufacturing is particularly high in the production of spare parts, since its introduction can reduce warehousing costs of slowly rotating spare parts.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Digitizing technology bears the potential to completely disrupt and restructure supply chains and enhance existing production routes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In comparison, research on the influence of blockchain technology on the supply chain is still in its early stages.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] literature has argued for a considerably long time that the highest performance efficacy is expected in the potential for automatic contract creation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition, traditional supply chain has many drawbacks such as lack of transparency and trust, and some of them can be solved by blockchain technology.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The technological features of blockchains support transparency and traceability of information, as well as high levels of reliability and immutability of records.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] have implemented blockchain-based traceability systems for agricultural and food supply chains in Taiwan.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] That helps traditional supply chain management to be more efficient and reliable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain systems configure value for those that organize the networks.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Value is the additional revenue over and above the costs of building the network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Co-creating value and sharing the benefits appropriately to encourage effective participation is a key challenge for any supply system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Tony Hines defines value as follows: "Ultimately it is the customer who pays the price for service delivered that confirms value and not the producer who simply adds cost until that point".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Global supply chains pose challenges regarding both quantity and value.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] These trends have many benefits for manufacturers because they make possible larger lot sizes, lower taxes, and better environments (e.g., culture, infrastructure, special tax zones, or sophisticated OEM) for their products.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] There are many additional challenges when the scope of supply chains is global.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] This is because with a supply chain of a larger scope, the lead time is much longer, and because there are more issues involved, such as multiple currencies, policies, and laws.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The consequent problems include different currencies and valuations in different countries, different tax laws, different trading protocols, vulnerability to natural disasters and cyber threats, and lack of transparency of cost and profit.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The disruptions in the existing international supply chain networks created by tariff increases in 2024-2025 were quantifiable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Shipping lines recorded large changes in cargo tonnage and trade routes when manufacturers reviewed the economic feasibility of marketed trade routes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] According to German shipping company Hapag-Lloyd, one in every three of the planned U.S.-bound shipments in China had been cancelled as a result of tariff announcements.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] These cancellations were one of the more drastic instances of instant supply chain change, providing unused capacity on trans-Pacific paths, and at the same time, placing additional stress on companies to find alternative sourcing deals.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The extent of disruption depended on the sector of the industry, and the most impacted was the labor-intensive manufacturing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Government officials had economic evaluations that pointed to other wider consequences than direct trade expenses.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The Finance Minister of Indonesia estimated that disruptions related to tariffs would decrease the GDP of the country by 0.3 to 0.5 percentage points.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] These projections represented fears of second-hand effects, such as reduced investment in business and slowed infrastructure development in export-related sectors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The countries that had high manufacturing export bases were under special pressure to diversify access to markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Not every economy had suffered equal adverse effects from the tariff environment.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The increase of Mexican manufacturing exports to the United States was about 9 percent between January and November 2025.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] However, automotive shipments were subject to special duties, whereas the non-automotive manufactured commodities showed better performance with 17% increase over the same period of time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] This was apparently a result of the reorientation of the supply chain, where production operations moved to areas where preferential trade status was being sustained by the jurisdictions.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Some of the observers were surprised by the pace of such reconfigurations, and this indicated that the supply chain was more flexible than was earlier thought.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Corporate adaptation practices were not just limited to mere geographical relocation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The documented responses were the reorganization of procurement networks, changes in the import process to streamline the tariff classification, and speedy sourcing activities in the region.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Some multinational companies developed parallel sourcing capacity in two or more locations - a back-up to maintain the flexibility of operations in the face of policy vagaries.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The economic implications of having duplicate supply chains made the long-term sustainability of such methods questionable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] These changes took place in compressed periods as compared to the conventional redesign of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Whereas major network restructuring normally takes several years to be implemented, tariff-based changes often need to be put in place within quarters.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] This speed challenged organizational agility to change and identified supply chain agility as a more and more important strategic ability.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] It was still a debatable issue whether those changes would continue to exist once the possible cut on tariffs would occur after all.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals play major roles in the design and management of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the design of supply chains, they help determine whether a product or service is provided by the firm itself (insourcing) or by another firm elsewhere (outsourcing).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the management of supply chains, supply chain professionals coordinate production among multiple providers, ensuring that production and transport of goods happen with minimal quality control or inventory problems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] One goal of a well-designed and maintained supply chain for a product is to successfully build the product at minimal cost.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Such a supply chain could be considered a competitive advantage for a firm.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Beyond design and maintenance of a supply chain itself, supply chain professionals participate in aspects of business that have a bearing on supply chains, such as sales forecasting, quality management, strategy development, customer service, and systems analysis.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Production of a good may evolve over time, rendering an existing supply chain design obsolete.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals need to be aware of changes in production and business climate that affect supply chains and create alternative supply chains as the need arises.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Keeping up with frequent changes in regulation was identified as a particular concern.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Complexity within supply chains has also been highlighted in *Supply Chain Digest* and by Gartner as a perennial challenge.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain consultants may provide expert knowledge in order to assess the productivity of a supply chain and, ideally, to enhance its productivity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In this regard, firms may either build internal teams of consultants to tackle the issue or engage external ones: companies choose between these two approaches taking into consideration various factors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The use of external consultants is a common practice among companies.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The whole consulting process generally involves the analysis of the entire supply chain process, including the countermeasures or correctives to take to achieve a better overall performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals need to have knowledge of managing supply chain functions such as transportation, warehousing, inventory management, and production planning.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the past, supply chain professionals emphasized logistics skills, such as knowledge of shipping routes, familiarity with warehousing equipment and distribution center locations and footprints, and a solid grasp of freight rates and fuel costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] More recently, supply chain management extends to logistical support across firms and management of global supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] A shortage of skilled supply chain professionals was highlighted in a study by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology published in 2010, which highlighted plentiful supply of staff with "narrow technical skillsets" but shortages in the numbers of job applicants with "broader business skills".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Individuals working in supply chain management can attain professional certification by passing an exam developed by a third party certification organization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The purpose of certification is to guarantee a certain level of expertise in the field.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The knowledge needed to pass a certification exam may be gained from several sources.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Some knowledge may come from college courses, but most of it is acquired from a mix of on-the-job learning experiences, attending industry events, learning best practices with their peers, and reading books and articles in the field.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Certification organizations may provide certification workshops tailored to their exams.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] In the same ranking, the following European universities rank high: Cranfield School of Management, Vlerick Business School, INSEAD, Cambridge University, Eindhoven University of Technology, London Business School and Copenhagen Business School.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] APICS' certification is called *Certified Supply Chain Professional*, or CSCP, and ISCEA's certification is called the *Certified Supply Chain Manager* (CSCM), CISCM (Chartered Institute of Supply Chain Management) awards certificate as *Chartered Supply Chain Management Professional* (CSCMP).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] Another, the Institute for Supply Management, is developing one called the *Certified Professional in Supply Management* (CPSM) focused on the procurement and sourcing areas of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The Supply Chain Management Association (SCMA) is the main certifying body for Canada with the designations having global reciprocity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain-management-p02] The designation Supply Chain Management Professional (SCMP) is the title of the supply chain leadership designation.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In sophisticated supply chain systems, the reintroduction of used products into the supply chain may occur at any point where the residual value of the product is recyclable.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Supply chains are linked to value chains, and suppliers within a supply chain are often organized into tiers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] First-tier suppliers, also referred to as "direct suppliers", directly supply goods or services to the client.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Second-tier suppliers supply to the first tier, and so on, creating a hierarchical structure within the supply network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The phrase "supply chain" may have been first published in a 1905 article in *The Independent*, which briefly mentioned the difficulty of "keeping a supply chain with India unbroken" during the British expedition to Tibet.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A typical supply chain can be divided into two stages namely, production and distribution stages.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In the production stage, components and semi-finished parts are produced in manufacturing centres.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The components are then put together in an assembly plant.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The distribution stage consists of central and regional distribution centres that transport products to end-consumers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Mentzer *et al.* suggest that at least three entities are required for there to be a "supply chain".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Many of the exchanges encountered in the supply chain take place between varied companies that seek to maximize their revenue within their sphere of interest but may have little or no knowledge or interest in the remaining players in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A chain is actually a complex and dynamic supply and demand network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] As part of their efforts to demonstrate ethical practices, many large companies and global brands are integrating codes of conduct and guidelines into their corporate cultures and management systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Through these, corporations are making demands on their suppliers (facilities, farms, subcontracted services such as cleaning, canteen, security etc.) and verifying, through social audits, that they are complying with the required standard.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A lack of transparency in the supply chain can bar consumers from knowledge of where their purchases originated and facilitate socially irresponsible practices.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In 2018, the Loyola University Chicago's Supply and Value Chain Center found in a survey that 53% of supply chain professionals considered ethics to be "extremely" important to their organizations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In some cases, the operation of multiple tiers within a supply chain may give rise to additional costs, due to the "profit layering", where each tier's operators add a profit margin to their costs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] For example, in 2015 the UK's Ministry of Justice recognised that its lift maintenance and refurbishment contracts were let to a main contractor who then sub-contracted the work to a specialist lift contractor.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The ministry avoided the cost impact of this arrangement by contracting for lift work directly with the specialist contractors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In each case, the flow of information and finances is part of the chain as well as the product or service.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Fazel Zarandi *et al.* add "buyer-seller relations" (at each stage), in addition to the flow of information, as the third main component of a supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Mentzer *et al.* remind readers also that the focus of a supply chain is on the product or service in its end state: they refer to "the supply chain for candy" and "the supply chain for clothing".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Individual supply chain actors may be positioned at different points in different supply chains: a bank, for example, may play a supporting role in certain supply chains, but acts as either the customer or the nearest supplier to the customer in the supply chain for security printing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply's professional guidance suggests that the aim of a tightly coupled relationship is to reduce inventory and avoid stock-outs.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] There are a variety of supply-chain models, which address both the upstream and downstream elements of supply-chain management (SCM).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The SCOR (Supply-Chain Operations Reference) model, developed by a consortium of industry and the non-profit Supply Chain Council (now part of APICS) became the cross-industry *de facto* standard defining the scope of supply-chain management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] SCOR measures total supply-chain performance.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] It is a process reference model for supply-chain management, extending "from the supplier's supplier to the customer's customer".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] It includes delivery and order fulfillment performance, production flexibility, warranty and returns processing costs, inventory and asset turns, and other factors in evaluating the overall effective performance of a supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A supply chain can often be split into different segments: the earlier stages of a supply chain, such as raw material processing and manufacturing, determine their break-even point by considering production costs relative to market price.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The later stages of a supply chain, such as wholesale and retail determine their break-even point by considering transaction costs, relative to market price.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Additionally, there are financial costs associated with all the stages of a supply chain model.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The Global Supply Chain Forum has introduced an alternative supply chain model.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] This framework is built on eight key business processes that are both cross-functional and cross-firm in nature.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Each process is managed by a cross-functional team including representatives from logistics, production, purchasing, finance, marketing, and research and development.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] While each process interfaces with key customers and suppliers, the processes of customer relationship management and supplier relationship management form the critical linkages in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The American Productivity and Quality Center (APQC) Process Classification Framework (PCF) SM is a high-level, industry-neutral enterprise process model that allows organizations to view their business processes from a cross-industry perspective.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The PCF was developed by APQC and its member organizations as an open standard to facilitate improvement through process management and benchmarking, regardless of industry, size, or geography.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The PCF organizes operating and management processes into 12 enterprise-level categories, including process groups, and over 1,000 processes and associated activities.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In the developing country public health setting, John Snow, Inc. has developed the JSI Framework for Integrated Supply Chain Management in Public Health, which draws from commercial sector best practices to solve problems in public health supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Similarly, supply chain mapping involves documenting information regarding all participants in an organization's supply chain and assembling the information as a global map of the organization's supply network.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In the 1980s, the term supply-chain management (SCM) was developed to express the need to integrate the key business processes, from end user through original suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Original suppliers are those that provide products, services, and information that add value for customers and other stakeholders.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The basic idea behind SCM is that companies and corporations involve themselves in a supply chain by exchanging information about market demand, distribution capacity and production capabilities.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Keith Oliver, a consultant at Booz Allen Hamilton, is credited with the term's invention after using it in an interview for the *Financial Times* in 1982.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The term was used earlier by Alizamir et al. in 1981, and Burns and Sivazlian in 1978.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] If all relevant information is accessible to any relevant company, every company in the supply chain has the ability to help optimize the entire supply chain rather than to sub-optimize based on local optimization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] This will lead to better-planned overall production and distribution, which can cut costs and give a more attractive final product, leading to better sales and better overall results for the companies involved.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] This is one form of vertical integration.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Yet, it has been shown that the motives for and performance efficacy of vertical integration differ by global region.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Incorporating SCM successfully leads to a new kind of competition on the global market, where competition is no longer of the company-versus-company form but rather takes on a supply-chain-versus-supply-chain form.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The primary objective of SCM is to fulfill customer demands through the most efficient use of resources, including distribution capacity, inventory, and labor.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In theory, a supply chain seeks to match demand with supply and do so with minimal inventory.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] However, John Mills *et al*. note that "early research" on supply chains focused on internal supply relationships within a company.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Starting in the 1990s, several companies chose to outsource the logistics aspect of supply-chain management by partnering with a third-party logistics provider (3PL).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Companies also outsource production to contract manufacturers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Technology companies have risen to meet the demand to help manage these complex systems.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Cloud-based SCM technologies are at the forefront of next-generation supply chains due to their impact on optimization of time, resources, and inventory visibility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Cloud technologies facilitate work being processed offline from a mobile app which solves the common issue of inventory residing in areas with no online coverage or connectivity.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Supply chain managers are under constant scrutiny to secure the best pricing for their resources, which becomes a difficult task when faced with the inherent lack of transparency.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Cost benchmarking helps to identify competitive pricing within the industry but benchmarking across a range of supply chain performance factors has been recommended as best practice.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The SCOR model contains more than 150 key indicators which measure the performance of supply chain operations: see also Supply chain operations reference#Performance measurements.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Debra Hofman has noted that "measuring supply chain performance is not a new practice.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Most companies today measure at least some aspect of their supply chain and understand the need for a more comprehensive measurement program." However, the abundance of options for potential performance metrics to use is seen as a challenge for supply chain managers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] One approach is to relate multiple measures in a hierarchical structure so that interdependencies and the contribution of multiple indicators to the "key" or most significant metrics can be more easily seen.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A Cranfield University boardroom survey in 2010 found evidence that many organizations recognized the importance of the supply chain contribution to their business success, with a focus on cost, customer lead-time and customer quality being the primary performance indicators.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Supply chain resilience is "the capacity of a supply chain to persist, adapt, or transform in the face of change".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] For a long time, the interpretation of resilience in the sense of engineering resilience (or robustness) prevailed in supply chain management, leading to the notion of *persistence*.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] A popular implementation of this idea is given by measuring the *time-to-survive* and the *time-to-recover* of the supply chain, allowing identification of weak points in the system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] For example, these three components of resilience can be identified in relation to the 2021 Suez Canal obstruction, when a ship blocked the canal for several days.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Finally, transformation means to question the assumptions of globalization, outsourcing, and linear supply chains and to envision alternatives; in this example this could lead to local and circular supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Supply chain resilience has been identified as an important business issue.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The United Kingdom's Confederation of British Industry reported in 2014 that a significant number of businesses had reshored parts of their supply chain to European locations, with many identifying supply chain resilience as "a key factor in their decision to do so".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Incidents like the 2013 Savar building collapse with more than 1,100 victims have led to widespread discussions about corporate social responsibility across global supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Wieland and Handfield (2013) suggest that companies need to audit products and suppliers and that supplier auditing needs to go beyond direct relationships with first-tier suppliers (those who supply the main customer directly).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] They also demonstrate that visibility needs to be improved if the supply cannot be directly controlled and that smart and electronic technologies play a key role to improve visibility.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Finally, they highlight that collaboration with local partners, across the industry and with universities is crucial to successfully manage social responsibility in supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] This incident also highlights the need to improve workers safety standards in organizations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Hoi and Lin (2012) note that corporate social responsibility can influence the enacting of policies that can improve occupational safety and health management in organizations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In fact, international organizations with presence in other nations have a responsibility to ensure that workers are well protected by policies in an organization to avoid safety related incidents.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Many agribusinesses and food processors source raw materials from smallholder farmers.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] This is particularly true in certain sectors, such as coffee, cocoa and sugar.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Over the past 20 years, there has been a shift towards more traceable supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Rather than purchasing crops that have passed through several layers of collectors, firms are now sourcing directly from farmers or trusted aggregators.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The drivers for this change include concerns about food safety, child labor and environmental sustainability as well as a desire to increase productivity and improve crop quality.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In October 2009, the European Commission issued a *Communication* concerning "a better functioning food supply chain in Europe", addressing the three sectors of the European economy which comprise the food supply chain: agriculture, food processing industries, and the distribution sectors.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] An earlier interim report on food prices (published in December 2008) had already raised concerns about the food supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Arising out of the two reports, the Commission established a "European Food Prices Monitoring Tool", an initiative developed by Eurostat and intended to "increase transparency in the food supply chain".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In March 2022 the Commission noted "the need for EU agriculture and food supply chains to become more resilient and sustainable".
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The supply chain in the fashion industries has some unique properties, as clothing fashion changes several times a year (often seasonally).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The supply chain for clothing often requires constant analysis of new fashion trends to manage the quantity needed for various markets.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Supply chain security has become particularly important in recent years.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] As a result, supply chains are often subject to global and local regulations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In the United States, several major regulations emerged in 2010 that have had a lasting impact on how global supply chains operate.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] These new regulations include the Importer Security Filing (ISF) and additional provisions of the Certified Cargo Screening Program.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] EU's draft supply chain law are due diligence requirements to protect human rights and the environment in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] The consulting firm Deloitte refers to more extensive supply chains emerging and greater complexity emerging due to increasing globalization of market access, along with seeing reconfiguration of supply chains as an observable trend.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Some supply chain reconfiguration has been undertaken for cost reduction purposes, but other objectives include speedier delivery to customers and the creation of new value-adding services.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] With easier access to different kinds of alternative products in today's markets, the contribution of product design to generating demand is more significant than ever.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In addition, as supply—and therefore competition—among companies for the limited market demand increases, and as pricing and other marketing elements become less distinguishing factors, product design plays a different role by providing attractive features to generate demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In this context, demand generation is used to define how attractive a product design is in terms of creating demand.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] In other words, it is the ability of a product's design to generate demand by satisfying customer expectations.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] However, product design affects not only demand generation but also manufacturing processes, cost, quality, and lead time.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Product design directly affects the associated supply chain and its requirements, including manufacturing, transportation, quality, quantity, production schedules, material selection, production technologies, production policies, regulations, and laws.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Broadly, the success of the supply chain depends on product design and the capabilities of the supply chain; the reverse is also true: the success of the product depends on the supply chain that produces it.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Big data is increasingly being utilized in supply chain management, especially in the strategic purchasing and supply management sector.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Determining the number of suppliers logically precedes an RFP process for determining *which* suppliers will form part of the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] Morgan refers to an "n + 1 rule" example in the business practice of IT component supplier Intel, whereby the maximum number of suppliers required to maintain production levels for each component is determined, and no more than one additional supplier is engaged with for each component.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/supply-chain] With the increased complexity and b2b activity associated with economic growth, actors often seek to view supply chain collaboration as a part of the value adding activities in a value chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] In the distribution and logistics of many types of products, **track and trace** or **tracking and tracing**, a type of tracking system that determines the current and past locations and other information of a unique item or property.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] **Mass serialization** is the process of assigning and marking each product with a unique identifier, such as an Electronic Product Code (EPC), for track and trace purposes.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] The marking or "tagging" of products is usually completed within the manufacturing process through various combinations of human-readable or machine-readable technologies such as DataMatrix barcodes or RFID.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] The track and trace concept is part of modern telematics and can be supported by a vehicle tracking system.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] This often relies on automatic vehicle location technology for vehicles and containers for the property of concern, with data stored in a real-time database.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] This data, a form of telemetry, is used for fleet management to compose a coherent depiction of status reports.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Another approach is to report the arrival or departure of the object, recording its identification, location, time, and status.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] This method requires verifying the reports for consistency and completeness.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] An example of this is the package tracking provided by shippers, such as the United States Postal Service, Deutsche Post, Royal Mail, United Parcel Service, AirRoad, or FedEx.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] These standards for tracking and tracing have been used in deployments in many industries, and many products are certified as compatible with them.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] In vehicular applications, tracking is often accomplished using a GPS tracking unit which communicates through a telematic control unit.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] More advanced systems incorporate video telematics, using devices like a dashcam to provide visual context for tracking events.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] In response to an increasing number of recall incidents for items like food, pharmaceuticals, and toys, vendors offer a range of traceability solutions and tools.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Radio-frequency identification and barcodes are two common technologies used to deliver traceability.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] RFID is often used in track-and-trace solutions and within supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] As a code-carrying technology, it can be used in place of a barcode to enable non-line-of-sight reading.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] The deployment of RFID was earlier inhibited by cost, but its usage is now increasing.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Barcoding is a common and cost-effective method used to implement traceability at both the item and case level.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Variable data in a barcode or a numeric or alphanumeric code format can be applied to the packaging or label.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] The data can be used as a pointer to traceability information and can also correlate with production data such as time to market and product quality.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Aggregation is an important step in pharmaceutical serialization.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] It links individual carton serial numbers to the shipper case or pallet in which they are packed, enabling efficient product traceability throughout the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Aggregation improves supply chain visibility and supports regulatory compliance by allowing manufacturers and distributors to identify the contents of a shipment without scanning every individual package.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Serialization supports supply chain agility, providing visibility into supply chain activities and the ability to take responsive action.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Benefits include the ability to recognize and isolate counterfeit products and to improve the efficiency of product recall management.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Consumers can access websites to trace the origins of their purchased products or to find the status of shipments.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] A user can type a code found on an item into a search box at a tracing website to view information.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] This can also be done via a smartphone by taking a picture of a 2D barcode, which opens a website that verifies the product (i.e., product authentication).
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] Serialization is used for safety in the pharmaceutical industry, where it is often legally required.
[src:supply-chain-visibility/track-and-trace] The same tracking principles are also used in wider intelligent transportation systems, in public transport to provide real-time arrival information, and to help power journey planners.
